<i>I think he has learned his lesson.</i>

242
00:18:42,414 --> 00:18:44,374
Come on, Henri. Let's go.

243
00:18:49,129 --> 00:18:51,423
<i>Henri Young had been rehabilitated.</i>

244
00:18:51,507 --> 00:18:55,761
<i>I was now a public defender
in San Francisco. We'd meet in three days.</i>

245
00:18:56,595 --> 00:18:57,679
Eat, Young!

246
00:18:58,388 --> 00:19:01,808
You know the rules!
You don't eat, you go to solitary!

247
00:19:03,977 --> 00:19:05,354
Now, get with it!

248
00:19:07,773 --> 00:19:09,608
<i>Two times two is four.</i>

249
00:19:10,234 --> 00:19:11,818
<i>Two times three is six.</i>

250
00:19:12,152 --> 00:19:14,154
<i>Two times four is eight.</i>

251
00:19:14,780 --> 00:19:15,906
<i>Eight.</i>

252
00:19:16,365 --> 00:19:17,908
<i>Two times five...</i>

253
00:19:18,242 --> 00:19:19,034
<i>...ten.</i>

254
00:19:20,285 --> 00:19:21,620
<i>Twelve times...</i>

255
00:19:21,870 --> 00:19:22,955
<i>...eight...</i>

256
00:19:24,790 --> 00:19:26,041
<i>...ninety-six.</i>

257
00:19:30,170 --> 00:19:32,840
<i>Maybe, maybe, maybe, maybe,
maybe more--</i>

258
00:19:38,804 --> 00:19:41,390
Henri, McCain, he put you in the hole.

259
00:19:41,640 --> 00:19:43,141
Put you in the hole.

260
00:19:43,392 --> 00:19:45,352
McCain's still here. Look!

261
00:19:45,602 --> 00:19:48,313
<i>McCain put you in the hole!
Put you in the hole!</i>

262
00:19:48,689 --> 00:19:51,942
<i>McCain, he put you in the hole.
Put you in the hole!</i>

263
00:20:31,356 --> 00:20:32,816
Get them back!

264
00:20:33,358 --> 00:20:35,819
Get them back against the wall now!

265
00:20:36,028 --> 00:20:37,362
Do it now!

266
00:20:38,363 --> 00:20:39,531
What happened?

267
00:20:39,740 --> 00:20:41,241
l don't know.

268
00:21:15,734 --> 00:21:18,529
<i>The United States of America
vs. Henri Young.</i>

269
00:21:18,987 --> 00:21:21,240
<i>Charged with murder in the first degree.</i>

270
00:21:21,281 --> 00:21:22,407
<i>Approach the bench.</i>

271
00:21:23,992 --> 00:21:26,537
Charged with murder in the first degree.

272
00:21:28,163 --> 00:21:31,750
''Henri Young, Rufus McCain...
and there, striking and wounding...

273
00:21:31,834 --> 00:21:34,586
''...sharp steel instrument...
to wit, a spoon.''

274
00:21:35,504 --> 00:21:37,172
No, this can't be right.

275
00:21:38,257 --> 00:21:39,174
lt's right.

276
00:21:39,258 --> 00:21:40,509
lf you say so.

277
00:21:40,634 --> 00:21:43,512
''To wit, a spoon
about four inches in length...

278
00:21:43,637 --> 00:21:46,849
''...which, striking and wounding,
described as foresaid...

279
00:21:46,932 --> 00:21:49,852
''...caused the said Rufus McCain
thereafter, to wit...

280
00:21:49,935 --> 00:21:52,896
''...on June 1 1, 1941 to die.''

281
00:21:54,147 --> 00:21:56,984
Trial set one week from Thursday, June 22.

282
00:21:57,943 --> 00:21:59,570
This court stands adjourned.

283
00:22:13,292 --> 00:22:15,085
l know you can do it!

284
00:22:17,880 --> 00:22:19,047
Come on, boy!

285
00:22:19,173 --> 00:22:21,967
You can do it! You've got four furlongs!

286
00:22:22,134 --> 00:22:24,052
Don't be cursing this street!

287
00:22:24,178 --> 00:22:28,140
Pick them up and lay them down!
Let those legs pump like pistons!

288
00:22:28,307 --> 00:22:32,269
Yes! Come on! The spirit is willing!
l can see it in your eyes.

289
00:22:33,103 --> 00:22:34,313
Come on!

290
00:22:35,105 --> 00:22:36,356
Pump it! Go!

291
00:22:36,565 --> 00:22:39,026
Remember Jesse Owens
at the '36 Olympics?

292
00:22:40,944 --> 00:22:42,654
Maybe tomorrow, sonny boy!

293
00:23:07,179 --> 00:23:08,722
Watch it, buster!

294
00:23:28,116 --> 00:23:29,451
Sorry, Counselor!

295
00:23:29,910 --> 00:23:31,453
You're all right?

296
00:23:32,037 --> 00:23:33,497
Mary, l'm sorry.

297
00:23:34,373 --> 00:23:36,375
l'm sorry. Mary, you okay?

298
00:23:36,625 --> 00:23:38,710
-Stop that!
-Okay, l'm sorry!

299
00:23:38,877 --> 00:23:42,256
lf Henkin saw us, he wouldn't think twice
about suspending us.

300
00:23:42,297 --> 00:23:43,757
-All right.
-Fix your tie.

301
00:23:43,841 --> 00:23:44,800
Why?

302
00:23:45,717 --> 00:23:47,761
You need to look good
when you thank Henkin.

303
00:23:47,886 --> 00:23:50,889
What do l want to thank Henkin for?
The man's a cretin.

304
00:23:51,139 --> 00:23:54,184
-He's given you a case.
-Case of what? Scotch?

305
00:23:54,434 --> 00:23:56,603
Yes, James, a case of Scotch.

306
00:23:56,770 --> 00:23:59,523
An actual case where l stand
in front of a jury?

307
00:24:00,148 --> 00:24:02,985
-Federal murder one, no less.
-Henri Young.

308
00:24:03,277 --> 00:24:07,239
He's a convict who killed another convict
in front of 200 witnesses.

309
00:24:08,949 --> 00:24:10,450
Was it self-defense?

310
00:24:10,576 --> 00:24:11,743
With a spoon.

311
00:24:11,827 --> 00:24:13,161
What with a spoon?

312
00:24:13,245 --> 00:24:16,498
That was the murder weapon.
He used a spoon to kill the man.

313
00:24:16,582 --> 00:24:19,001
Weren't any forks or knives available?

314
00:24:19,084 --> 00:24:21,003
My first case l can't possibly win.

315
00:24:21,086 --> 00:24:25,007
Do this one for the experience, for the next
time, when maybe your guy didn't do it.

316
00:24:25,132 --> 00:24:26,425
You could learn a lot.

317
00:24:26,466 --> 00:24:28,594
Go see your client
and make nice to Henkin.

318
00:24:28,719 --> 00:24:30,888
-l'll see you tonight?
-Maybe.

319
00:24:33,307 --> 00:24:36,393
Thank you for your confidence in me
in getting this case.

320
00:24:36,476 --> 00:24:39,688
l don't have any confidence in you.
The guy is guilty.

321
00:24:39,813 --> 00:24:43,108
A monkey could try this case
and not make it any worse.

322
00:24:43,192 --> 00:24:45,068
-l see.
-Remember that.

323
00:24:45,277 --> 00:24:46,987
-Thank you, sir.
-A monkey.

324
00:24:49,198 --> 00:24:50,782
l guess l'm a monkey.

325
00:25:10,302 --> 00:25:14,056
-James Stamphill to see Henri Young.
-l need you to sign the release.

326
00:25:17,643 --> 00:25:19,853
-lt's a nice day.
-Yeah, great.

327
00:25:51,510 --> 00:25:52,928
Where are you going?

328
00:25:53,011 --> 00:25:54,763
To the cell, talk to my client.

329
00:25:54,847 --> 00:25:56,265
What, are you nuts?

330
00:25:56,348 --> 00:25:58,517
l want to speak to him face to face.

331
00:25:59,726 --> 00:26:00,686
Well....

332
00:26:02,896 --> 00:26:05,023
You've already signed the release.

333
00:26:10,612 --> 00:26:11,947
lt's your life.

334
00:26:16,702 --> 00:26:17,661
Hi.

335
00:26:18,871 --> 00:26:20,914
So, then, Mr. Young, is it?

336
00:26:23,208 --> 00:26:25,335
You're Mr. Young, is that correct?

337
00:26:27,212 --> 00:26:29,339
Mr. Young, that is your name, isn't it?

338
00:26:29,423 --> 00:26:30,549
Henri Young?

339
00:26:33,343 --> 00:26:37,222
l'll just assume that's your name
until you tell me differently.

340
00:26:37,598 --> 00:26:40,475
Mr. Young, l will be acting
as your defense attorney.

341
00:26:40,559 --> 00:26:43,103
l'm James Stamphill
and anything you tell me...

342
00:26:43,228 --> 00:26:46,815
...will be protected under the rules
of confidentiality...

343
00:26:46,940 --> 00:26:50,068
...of the attorney-client relationship.
So feel completely free...

344
00:26:50,194 --> 00:26:53,488
...to answer my questions
in an honest and forthright fashion.

345
00:26:53,572 --> 00:26:56,867
Just for the record,
your name is Henri Young, right?

346
00:27:01,163 --> 00:27:04,499
This isn't an admission of guilt.
lt's just your name.

347
00:27:06,376 --> 00:27:07,753
You speak English?

348
00:27:09,630 --> 00:27:13,217
Yeah, you do speak English.
lt says so right here in the file.

349
00:27:19,932 --> 00:27:21,099
Mr. Young...

350
00:27:22,809 --> 00:27:27,481
...l am your attorney but l can't provide you
with much of a defense if one of us is...

351
00:27:27,981 --> 00:27:29,191
...catatonic.

352
00:27:30,108 --> 00:27:31,276
You see...

353
00:27:31,693 --> 00:27:35,656
...we both have to be able and willing
to answer when our name is called.

354
00:27:39,368 --> 00:27:40,827
Can you hear?

355
00:27:58,387 --> 00:27:59,638
Mr. Young?

356
00:28:01,640 --> 00:28:03,141
You okay, Mr. Young?

357
00:28:03,350 --> 00:28:05,978
<i>Henri Young was born in Kansas in 1913.</i>

358
00:28:07,646 --> 00:28:09,982
<i>His parents died ten years later...</i>

359
00:28:10,023 --> 00:28:12,317
<i>...leaving Henri to raise his younger sister.</i>

360
00:28:13,569 --> 00:28:17,281
<i>At the age of 17, Henri went into
a local store to try to get a job.</i>

361
00:28:19,074 --> 00:28:20,826
<i>He was refused work.</i>

362
00:28:22,202 --> 00:28:26,123
<i>Out of desperation he reached
into the cash register and took $5.</i>

363
00:28:27,416 --> 00:28:30,502
<i>The store also doubled
as the town's post office.</i>

364
00:28:31,920 --> 00:28:35,883
<i>Henri was tried and convicted
of the federal crime of mail robbery.</i>

365
00:28:37,509 --> 00:28:40,387
<i>Henri's sister was taken
to live in an orphanage.</i>

366
00:28:42,306 --> 00:28:44,183
<i>He would never see her again.</i>

367
00:28:45,893 --> 00:28:48,812
<i>Eleven years later,
Henri would kill Rufus McCain.</i>

368
00:29:16,048 --> 00:29:17,341
Mr. Young...

369
00:29:17,758 --> 00:29:19,718
...you killed a guy, so...

370
00:29:20,302 --> 00:29:22,221
...you're not catatonic.

371
00:29:24,515 --> 00:29:26,475
l know that you can talk.

372
00:29:27,476 --> 00:29:28,936
l don't know...

373
00:29:29,937 --> 00:29:32,397
...maybe you could write something.

374
00:29:35,025 --> 00:29:37,528
You want to write something? Write here.

375
00:29:40,656 --> 00:29:42,324
Something. Just....

376
00:29:43,408 --> 00:29:45,452
Look, you want to give it a try?

377
00:29:45,619 --> 00:29:47,204
You want to write?

378
00:29:51,750 --> 00:29:53,085
Something...

379
00:29:53,252 --> 00:29:54,461
...please.

380
00:29:56,505 --> 00:29:58,757
Mr. Young, you're looking at me.

381
00:29:59,091 --> 00:30:00,926
You hear me, don't you?

382
00:30:03,428 --> 00:30:07,099
lf you won't answer my questions,
maybe we can start with something else.

383
00:30:07,224 --> 00:30:09,977
What do you want?
There has to be something.

384
00:30:10,060 --> 00:30:14,064
Can't be to sit there, because if you do,
they'll just stick you in the gas chamber.

385
00:30:14,147 --> 00:30:15,774
Do you understand that?

386
00:30:29,121 --> 00:30:30,080
Look...

387
00:30:32,165 --> 00:30:34,293
...Mr. Young, l've read your file.

388
00:30:35,711 --> 00:30:37,713
l am trying to help you.

389
00:30:38,505 --> 00:30:41,466
That's all l'm trying to do.
l just want to help you.

390
00:30:42,134 --> 00:30:43,552
Maybe there are...

391
00:30:44,094 --> 00:30:46,638
...extenuating circumstances in your case.

392
00:30:48,724 --> 00:30:51,476
Getting sentenced to Leavenworth
for stealing...

393
00:30:51,643 --> 00:30:53,604
...$500, that's extenuating.

394
00:30:58,692 --> 00:31:01,278
You have to understand, l'm on your side.

395
00:31:01,570 --> 00:31:02,404
$5.

396
00:31:02,487 --> 00:31:03,822
What, Mr. Young?

397
00:31:05,866 --> 00:31:07,826
lt was $5, not $500.

398
00:31:08,952 --> 00:31:12,831
l knew you had it in you. Now, come on.
Why did you kill Rufus McCain?

399
00:31:13,749 --> 00:31:16,251
You just talked. Don't do this again.

400
00:31:16,960 --> 00:31:20,130
Come on, don't quit now.
Come on, you just talked!

401
00:31:20,672 --> 00:31:22,299
Why did you kill McCain?

402
00:31:28,597 --> 00:31:29,556
What?

403
00:31:30,516 --> 00:31:32,351
-What are you saying?
-How....

404
00:31:32,392 --> 00:31:33,936
How? How? How?

405
00:31:34,728 --> 00:31:36,188
Are you saying ''how''?

406
00:31:36,230 --> 00:31:37,272
How.

407
00:31:37,898 --> 00:31:38,857
How?

408
00:31:39,525 --> 00:31:40,526
How.

409
00:31:42,027 --> 00:31:45,948
How. What are you, a fucking lndian?
Don't quit now. How what?

410
00:31:46,073 --> 00:31:46,907
How is....

411
00:31:46,990 --> 00:31:50,619
You want to know how somebody is?
l'll find out immediately.

412
00:31:51,036 --> 00:31:52,037
How is....

413
00:31:52,663 --> 00:31:53,455
Who?

414
00:31:53,539 --> 00:31:54,706
DiMaggio.

415
00:31:55,123 --> 00:31:56,667
How is DiMaggio?

416
00:31:57,125 --> 00:31:59,211
ls he a prisoner over at Alcatraz?

417
00:31:59,878 --> 00:32:00,879
How is...

418
00:32:01,129 --> 00:32:02,422
...DiMaggio...

419
00:32:02,631 --> 00:32:04,091
...doing this year?

420
00:32:05,884 --> 00:32:08,095
DiMaggio, the baseball player?

421
00:32:08,637 --> 00:32:09,596
Yeah.

422
00:32:11,139 --> 00:32:15,686
How is Joe DiMaggio, the baseball player,
doing? That's what you're asking?

423
00:32:22,776 --> 00:32:24,152
Mr. Young...

424
00:32:27,739 --> 00:32:29,575
...l don't really follow baseball.

425
00:32:31,076 --> 00:32:32,119
You know.

426
00:32:42,337 --> 00:32:45,007
<i>Excuse me, Mr. McNeil,
I'm James Stamphill.</i>

427
00:32:46,175 --> 00:32:48,135
-Counsel for Henri Young.
-Yes.

428
00:32:48,218 --> 00:32:51,180
l was wondering if l could talk to you
about continuance?

429
00:32:51,263 --> 00:32:52,222
No.

430
00:32:52,306 --> 00:32:55,100
You don't understand.
He just sits there and won't speak.

431
00:32:55,184 --> 00:32:59,146
Maybe he's practicing for the gas chamber.
Tell him to take deep breaths.

432
00:32:59,271 --> 00:33:02,941
You won't even consider a joint motion
in the interest of justice?

433
00:33:03,442 --> 00:33:06,361
-Are you old enough to be a lawyer?
-Yes, sir, l am.

434
00:33:06,445 --> 00:33:08,822
No joint motion for a continuance.

435
00:33:08,989 --> 00:33:12,034
No psychiatrist.
And trust me, pal, no plea bargain.

436
00:33:12,201 --> 00:33:13,869
Your boy's gonna suck the pipe.

437
00:33:14,453 --> 00:33:17,998
l don't know who you pissed off
to get this shit case and l don't care.

438
00:33:18,123 --> 00:33:19,082
No breaks.

439
00:33:29,259 --> 00:33:32,012
Mr. Young, DiMaggio is having
a great year.

440
00:33:32,262 --> 00:33:35,766
Last year he was the American League
batting champ with a .352 average...

441
00:33:35,849 --> 00:33:40,145
...which was just a bit off the year before
when he had a .381 average.

442
00:33:40,312 --> 00:33:42,648
The Yankees, they too had a good year.

443
00:33:43,106 --> 00:33:45,234
New York defeated Chicago 4-0...

444
00:33:45,984 --> 00:33:48,737
...led by jolting Joe DiMaggio hitting 400.

445
00:33:49,655 --> 00:33:51,740
400, that's pretty good, isn't it?

446
00:33:53,659 --> 00:33:55,410
June 1 7, 1941 ...

447
00:33:56,036 --> 00:33:59,498
...our friend DiMaggio hits safely
in 32 straight games.

448
00:34:00,040 --> 00:34:03,335
Twelve more and he will tie
Wee Willie Keeler's all-time record...

449
00:34:03,377 --> 00:34:06,713
...who set the mark in 1897
for the Baltimore Orioles.

450
00:34:07,047 --> 00:34:11,510
Joe Louis was the victor in what some
consider the toughest win of his career.

451
00:34:17,933 --> 00:34:20,561
Here we go.
Here's some entertainment news.

452
00:34:20,686 --> 00:34:21,854
Betty Grable.

453
00:34:22,020 --> 00:34:23,021
See?

454
00:34:25,691 --> 00:34:27,484
Says here she's just--

455
00:34:28,569 --> 00:34:29,736
How old are you?

456
00:34:29,862 --> 00:34:31,196
What, Mr. Young?

457
00:34:32,281 --> 00:34:33,740
How old are you?

458
00:34:35,367 --> 00:34:36,702
l'm 24.

459
00:34:40,581 --> 00:34:41,915
l think...

460
00:34:42,708 --> 00:34:44,042
...l am too.

461
00:34:46,879 --> 00:34:48,046
No, you're...

462
00:34:49,089 --> 00:34:50,591
...you're 28.

463
00:35:04,938 --> 00:35:07,733
Would you like me to keep reading to you?

464
00:35:17,075 --> 00:35:20,162
This ought to make you
a little bit more comfortable.

465
00:35:35,677 --> 00:35:39,640
The defense requests a new jury.
Having been eliminated from this process--

466
00:35:39,765 --> 00:35:41,141
Three new members.

467
00:35:41,266 --> 00:35:42,601
And that's it.

468
00:35:43,101 --> 00:35:44,061
Next.

469
00:35:45,312 --> 00:35:48,273
The defense requests a continuance
of 60 days...

470
00:35:48,315 --> 00:35:50,192
...so l may confer with my client--

471
00:35:50,442 --> 00:35:52,402
He doesn't need 60 days.

472
00:35:52,653 --> 00:35:55,656
The facts in this case are so clear,
six minutes should do it.

473
00:35:55,781 --> 00:35:58,033
My client has been almost catatonic.

474
00:35:58,158 --> 00:36:01,036
-Yesterday was the first day--
-He wasn't so catatonic...

475
00:36:01,119 --> 00:36:05,457
...that he couldn't walk over and slit
a guy's throat in front of 200 witnesses.

476
00:36:06,291 --> 00:36:09,711
ls it your contention
that the defendant is insane?

477
00:36:09,962 --> 00:36:12,339
ls that what you mean by ''catatonic''?

478
00:36:13,674 --> 00:36:15,676
Approach the bench, Counselor.

479
00:36:18,637 --> 00:36:20,305
ls this laying the groundwork...

480
00:36:20,430 --> 00:36:23,100
...for a not-guilty by reason
of insanity plea?

481
00:36:23,809 --> 00:36:27,271
l don't know yet. l haven't even spoken
to him about the case--

482
00:36:27,855 --> 00:36:29,439
One week, Counselor.

483
00:36:29,523 --> 00:36:32,985
Then you will either tell me
you are ready for the trial...

484
00:36:33,151 --> 00:36:37,114
...or you will come in here with a request
for a competency hearing.

485
00:36:37,322 --> 00:36:38,532
One week.

486
00:36:40,826 --> 00:36:42,786
This court is in recess.

487
00:36:58,677 --> 00:37:01,305
Mr. Young, you and me,
we've got to talk now.

488
00:37:02,014 --> 00:37:03,849
Would you like a cigarette?

489
00:37:03,932 --> 00:37:05,309
No, thanks.

490
00:37:05,684 --> 00:37:07,436
That shit will kill you.

491
00:37:08,854 --> 00:37:09,897
That's...

492
00:37:10,063 --> 00:37:11,523
...kind of funny.

493
00:37:12,191 --> 00:37:13,859
''That shit'll kill you.''

494
00:37:14,234 --> 00:37:17,696
l'll die in that gas chamber anyway,
so that's kind of a joke.

495
00:37:17,863 --> 00:37:20,324
What's this about Nazis? We at war?

496
00:37:20,657 --> 00:37:22,534
No, not yet, Mr. Young.

497
00:37:22,868 --> 00:37:24,203
-lt's brand new.
-What?

498
00:37:24,244 --> 00:37:26,413
-Mr. Glenn told me.
-The associate warden?

499
00:37:26,538 --> 00:37:30,042
He says it's brand new.
He said they're gonna try it out on me.

500
00:37:34,254 --> 00:37:35,255
No.

501
00:37:37,090 --> 00:37:38,884
You only have a week.

502
00:37:39,218 --> 00:37:41,345
You've got to talk to me. Okay?

503
00:37:42,095 --> 00:37:44,097
Why did you kill Rufus McCain?

504
00:37:45,766 --> 00:37:47,976
Why did you kill Rufus McCain?

505
00:37:52,064 --> 00:37:54,608
How could you not know about baseball?

506
00:37:56,902 --> 00:37:59,238
You said, ''l don't follow baseball.''

507
00:37:59,279 --> 00:38:01,281
-How could you not?
-Why'd you kill him?

508
00:38:01,406 --> 00:38:04,952
Over and over, it must have been
maybe a year, l don't know.

509
00:38:05,077 --> 00:38:07,037
All l did was hear them in my head.

510
00:38:07,120 --> 00:38:10,499
What are you talking about?
Are you talking about McCain?

511
00:38:10,624 --> 00:38:14,086
l'm talking about baseball.
The great American pastime.

512
00:38:14,586 --> 00:38:17,548
l went over every game
l ever heard on the radio.

513
00:38:18,257 --> 00:38:22,261
l went over every game l ever heard.
Just playing them over in my head.

514
00:38:24,096 --> 00:38:26,056
You had all those games to go to...

515
00:38:26,139 --> 00:38:28,225
...and you didn't even care.

516
00:38:28,433 --> 00:38:30,394
l'm talking about Rufus McCain.

517
00:38:30,519 --> 00:38:34,106
l'm talking about three fucking years
they had me in that bucket!

518
00:38:34,481 --> 00:38:36,066
Three fucking years!

519
00:38:36,316 --> 00:38:40,279
Without any fucking light!
You had all those games to listen to!

520
00:38:41,446 --> 00:38:44,491
You didn't even know
what DiMaggio hit this year.

521
00:38:46,451 --> 00:38:48,328
What kind of asshole are you?

522
00:38:49,955 --> 00:38:51,415
Calm down, boy!

523
00:38:53,876 --> 00:38:57,212
You know the average length of time
an inmate would be in solitary?

524
00:38:57,296 --> 00:38:58,297
Nineteen days.

525
00:38:58,839 --> 00:39:00,966
l understand, but he killed a man.

526
00:39:01,049 --> 00:39:04,052
Henry did three years in total darkness.
ln a black hole.

527
00:39:04,178 --> 00:39:07,764
That's tragic, but he took a life.
Your brother will tell you what l did.

528
00:39:07,848 --> 00:39:10,726
-You won't get him off.
-He's the best lawyer l know.

529
00:39:10,809 --> 00:39:14,855
He can tell me if we've got a chance
for some kind of insanity plea.

530
00:39:14,980 --> 00:39:16,940
Your brother won't give a damn.

531
00:39:17,024 --> 00:39:18,984
<i>Your client is a two-time loser.</i>

532
00:39:19,193 --> 00:39:22,779
This case is much more
about you than him.

533
00:39:23,405 --> 00:39:24,948
He has no future.

534
00:39:25,616 --> 00:39:29,161
This is your first time in the spotlight.
lt's what you worked for.

535
00:39:29,494 --> 00:39:31,580
This case is a lost cause...

536
00:39:31,872 --> 00:39:34,750
...so you must handle it like a lost cause.

537
00:39:41,590 --> 00:39:45,093
Maybe you're right,
but the guy's not exactly Al Capone.

538
00:39:45,761 --> 00:39:47,095
No, he isn't.

539
00:39:48,055 --> 00:39:51,475
All they had him on was
income tax evasion. Your boy...

540
00:39:52,434 --> 00:39:54,269
...they got on murder one.

541
00:39:55,229 --> 00:39:55,979
Hi.

542
00:39:56,104 --> 00:39:57,231
How are you?

543
00:39:57,981 --> 00:39:58,982
Hi, Henri.

544
00:39:59,233 --> 00:40:00,359
Listen.

545
00:40:00,567 --> 00:40:03,612
You're not mad at me
for blowing up at you yesterday?

546
00:40:03,737 --> 00:40:05,239
Nobody talks back.

547
00:40:05,364 --> 00:40:06,907
No, l'm not mad at you.

548
00:40:07,074 --> 00:40:08,492
l'll get the hang of it.

549
00:40:08,575 --> 00:40:10,035
l got a sense of humor.

550
00:40:10,118 --> 00:40:12,704
We gonna have some good times
before this is through.

551
00:40:12,788 --> 00:40:15,457
You know how to play cards?
Could you get some?

552
00:40:15,958 --> 00:40:17,709
l set this up for you. Sit down.

553
00:40:17,793 --> 00:40:20,671
How much light got into the cell
you spent three years in?

554
00:40:20,754 --> 00:40:24,174
-Like when you offered me a cigarette.
-l want to get that straight.

555
00:40:24,258 --> 00:40:25,676
That was pretty good, huh?

556
00:40:26,301 --> 00:40:28,720
You gotta help me if l'm going
to defend you now.

557
00:40:28,804 --> 00:40:30,389
Yeah, sure, sure.

558
00:40:31,807 --> 00:40:33,225
Have a look here.

559
00:40:35,143 --> 00:40:37,896
Did you kill this man here? Rufus McCain?

560
00:40:39,439 --> 00:40:41,233
l must have. l'm here.

561
00:40:41,733 --> 00:40:44,653
l don't remember it,
but everybody saw me, so, yeah.

562
00:40:44,903 --> 00:40:46,989
-But you don't remember it?
-No. So what?

563
00:40:47,114 --> 00:40:48,323
Did you want to?

564
00:40:48,448 --> 00:40:51,493
Once there was this spider
that crawled over me.

565
00:40:51,785 --> 00:40:53,287
lt was like having company.

566
00:40:53,412 --> 00:40:56,331
l looked for him again, couldn't find him.
He had a way out.

567
00:40:56,456 --> 00:40:58,709
McCain landed you in the bucket, right?

568
00:40:58,792 --> 00:41:00,919
142 times 93. Ask me that one.

569
00:41:01,003 --> 00:41:04,298
-How long after you came out--
-13,206.

570
00:41:05,174 --> 00:41:08,135
13,000? You mean, days?
What are you talking about?

571
00:41:08,343 --> 00:41:10,929
No, that's the answer. 142 times 93.

572
00:41:11,013 --> 00:41:14,057
-Concentrate on what l'm saying!
-l know what you're saying.

573
00:41:14,141 --> 00:41:17,352
-How long was it?
-l don't know! l don't remember!

574
00:41:18,478 --> 00:41:21,273
Who's the new girl l've seen in the papers?
lngrid Berger?

575
00:41:21,356 --> 00:41:23,692
She's a looker. You seen her movies?

576
00:41:23,859 --> 00:41:25,277
l want you to think!

577
00:41:25,360 --> 00:41:26,904
l don't want to think!

578
00:41:27,112 --> 00:41:29,948
l spent three goddamn years in the dark...

579
00:41:30,199 --> 00:41:32,326
...smelling my own shit and piss...

580
00:41:32,534 --> 00:41:34,286
...doing nothing but thinking!

581
00:41:34,369 --> 00:41:35,829
l hate thinking!

582
00:41:42,794 --> 00:41:44,379
l'm sorry, Henri.

583
00:41:49,885 --> 00:41:51,220
l'm sorry.

584
00:41:52,679 --> 00:41:54,556
l'm just trying to help you.

585
00:41:55,933 --> 00:41:57,351
You got a girl, right?

586
00:41:58,852 --> 00:42:00,312
Take your jacket off.

587
00:42:00,854 --> 00:42:02,564
-What?
-Let me smell it.

588
00:42:03,023 --> 00:42:05,317
You were easier to understand catatonic.

589
00:42:05,400 --> 00:42:06,693
What's she like?

590
00:42:06,777 --> 00:42:08,654
-Who?
-Your girl. That's perfume.

591
00:42:08,695 --> 00:42:10,364
Let me smell your jacket.

592
00:42:12,574 --> 00:42:14,076
l'll make you a deal.

593
00:42:14,201 --> 00:42:17,621
l'll give my jacket, my pants,
whatever you want. Sports, girls....

594
00:42:17,704 --> 00:42:20,749
But you gotta tell me just one memory
about something l ask.

595
00:42:21,083 --> 00:42:22,125
Deal?

596
00:42:22,709 --> 00:42:23,710
Sure.

597
00:42:31,927 --> 00:42:33,762
l've never been with a girl.

598
00:42:41,228 --> 00:42:42,688
Let me try it on.

599
00:42:43,772 --> 00:42:46,233
How long was it you went
without any daylight?

600
00:42:46,358 --> 00:42:49,027
<i>Did they ever let you out for any exercise?</i>

601
00:42:49,444 --> 00:42:51,780
-Merry Christmas.
-Please, don't hit me.

602
00:42:51,947 --> 00:42:54,700
-Get the tear gas.
-How long l been in here?

603
00:42:54,908 --> 00:42:57,786
-You're out of the hole.
-l made it! l did it!

604
00:42:57,953 --> 00:42:59,496
lt's Christmas, 1940.

605
00:42:59,746 --> 00:43:01,748
You've been down there two years.

606
00:43:03,083 --> 00:43:04,251
Two years!

607
00:43:05,085 --> 00:43:06,253
l did it.

608
00:43:07,629 --> 00:43:09,089
Two fucking years.

609
00:43:10,090 --> 00:43:12,050
l made it. l made it.

610
00:43:12,926 --> 00:43:14,678
l'm not too crazy, am l?

611
00:43:15,470 --> 00:43:17,264
l did it! lt's over!

612
00:43:17,639 --> 00:43:19,349
Nothing's over, Henri.

613
00:43:19,433 --> 00:43:21,977
Thirty minutes exercise, that's all you get.

614
00:43:22,978 --> 00:43:23,979
No!

615
00:43:28,483 --> 00:43:30,485
You don't want it, we take you back.

616
00:43:30,569 --> 00:43:31,528
No!

617
00:43:31,945 --> 00:43:32,988
l want it!

618
00:43:33,197 --> 00:43:34,489
l want it.

619
00:43:35,991 --> 00:43:38,285
l'll be good. l'll be good.

620
00:43:46,835 --> 00:43:49,171
<i>Ladies and gentlemen of the jury:</i>

621
00:43:49,463 --> 00:43:51,465
<i>The defendant, Henri Young...</i>

622
00:43:51,507 --> 00:43:54,468
<i>...is accused of murder in the first degree.</i>

623
00:43:54,968 --> 00:43:58,555
<i>It is your responsibility,
as a juror, to deal with truth.</i>

624
00:43:59,515 --> 00:44:01,141
<i>Rufus McCain was murdered...</i>

625
00:44:02,309 --> 00:44:03,936
<i>...by Henri Young.</i>

626
00:44:04,019 --> 00:44:05,562
<i>Mr. Stamphill...</i>

627
00:44:05,979 --> 00:44:07,314
<i>...public defender...</i>

628
00:44:07,397 --> 00:44:11,360
<i>...will play upon your sympathies.
He'll use every trick in the book.</i>

629
00:44:11,485 --> 00:44:12,486
<i>Why?</i>

630
00:44:13,403 --> 00:44:15,239
<i>To avoid the gas chamber.</i>

631
00:44:15,822 --> 00:44:18,283
<i>The United States of America
will demand...</i>

632
00:44:18,492 --> 00:44:20,911
<i>...that you return a verdict of guilty...</i>

633
00:44:20,994 --> 00:44:22,621
<i>...so that this...</i>

634
00:44:22,996 --> 00:44:24,540
<i>...this animal...</i>

635
00:44:24,706 --> 00:44:27,918
<i>...will receive the punishment
commanded by the Bible.</i>

636
00:44:28,210 --> 00:44:29,837
<i>''An eye for an eye.''</i>

637
00:44:30,712 --> 00:44:32,339
<i>A life for a life.</i>

638
00:44:32,464 --> 00:44:35,425
<i>For if ever there was a man
guilty of murder...</i>

639
00:44:36,885 --> 00:44:38,428
...it is Henri Young.

640
00:44:39,680 --> 00:44:42,933
And if ever a man deserved
to die for that crime...

641
00:44:44,184 --> 00:44:45,978
...it is the accused.

642
00:44:49,815 --> 00:44:52,150
Thank you very much, Mr. McNeil.

643
00:44:54,903 --> 00:44:58,824
Mr. Stamphill, are you prepared
to make your opening statement?

644
00:44:59,533 --> 00:45:00,701
Your Honor...

645
00:45:01,034 --> 00:45:03,161
...ladies and gentlemen of the jury:

646
00:45:04,705 --> 00:45:08,542
When l was a kid, my heroes
weren't Babe Ruth or Lou Gehrig...

647
00:45:09,126 --> 00:45:11,253
...they were Clarence Darrow
and Émile Zola.

648
00:45:11,378 --> 00:45:14,298
ln other words, l have waited
for this moment all my life.

649
00:45:14,381 --> 00:45:17,509
To stand, like l am, in front of a jury
of 12 good people...

650
00:45:17,593 --> 00:45:21,263
...to plead the case of an innocent man
who's been unjustly accused.

651
00:45:21,388 --> 00:45:23,348
The only problem is he did it.

652
00:45:24,057 --> 00:45:26,852
l know it, the prosecutor, Mr. McNeil,
knows it.

653
00:45:27,060 --> 00:45:31,398
Henri doesn't know it 'cause he can't
remember it, but he won't deny he did it.

654
00:45:31,523 --> 00:45:34,860
All those witnesses the prosecutor
will bring forth will tell you...

655
00:45:34,943 --> 00:45:37,362
...Henri Young killed Rufus McCain.

656
00:45:38,447 --> 00:45:41,909
Now that we all know that,
why don't we find the man guilty...

657
00:45:41,950 --> 00:45:45,204
...and gas him because that's
what we all know is going to happen?

658
00:45:45,287 --> 00:45:46,455
Right, Henri?

659
00:45:46,580 --> 00:45:47,539
What?

660
00:45:48,874 --> 00:45:53,337
There's only one problem that'll keep us
from wrapping this up in record time.

661
00:45:53,629 --> 00:45:57,508
Henri Young did not act alone.
They haven't caught all the killers.

662
00:45:57,591 --> 00:46:02,346
There was a co-conspirator. Because of
this co-conspirator, whom we shall name...

663
00:46:02,596 --> 00:46:05,390
...Henri Young is innocent
of the crime of murder.

664
00:46:05,474 --> 00:46:06,517
What?

665
00:46:06,642 --> 00:46:09,102
Objection, Your Honor! l must protest!

666
00:46:09,269 --> 00:46:10,729
l figured you would.

667
00:46:10,812 --> 00:46:12,481
This is absurd.

668
00:46:12,856 --> 00:46:16,818
Before the counselor is allowed to waste
this court's time and this jury's time...

669
00:46:16,944 --> 00:46:21,490
...l'd request that he supply some proof
or evidence of this co-conspirator.

670
00:46:21,823 --> 00:46:25,953
Can you bring forward evidence
of the existence of a co-conspirator?

671
00:46:26,328 --> 00:46:30,332
Not at this time, but it is my intention
to do so during the course of the trial.

672
00:46:30,457 --> 00:46:34,253
He's not going to provide such proof
because no proof exists.

673
00:46:34,461 --> 00:46:37,631
This man spent three years
in solitary confinement...

674
00:46:37,840 --> 00:46:40,801
...during which time no one had
any influence over him...

675
00:46:40,884 --> 00:46:43,512
...because no one had
any contact with him.

676
00:46:44,137 --> 00:46:47,099
He came out of solitary.
He went directly to a shower.

677
00:46:47,182 --> 00:46:51,562
Then he went directly to a haircut.
Then he went directly to the dining hall...

678
00:46:51,645 --> 00:46:54,606
...where one convict had said
one sentence to him.

679
00:46:54,815 --> 00:46:57,276
This does not a co-conspirator make.

680
00:46:57,484 --> 00:47:00,362
l'm inclined to agree with the prosecution.

681
00:47:00,988 --> 00:47:03,282
Unless you can justify
that line of defense...

682
00:47:03,365 --> 00:47:06,118
...l will sustain the prosecution's objection.

683
00:47:06,326 --> 00:47:10,330
The district attorney, with his own words,
has just made my case for me.

684
00:47:10,539 --> 00:47:11,999
That'll be the day.

685
00:47:12,666 --> 00:47:13,834
Your Honor...

686
00:47:14,543 --> 00:47:17,671
...for three years,
three long, tortuous years...

687
00:47:18,046 --> 00:47:21,717
...no one and nothing had any influence
whatsoever over Henri Young.

688
00:47:22,009 --> 00:47:23,510
No one and nothing.

689
00:47:23,719 --> 00:47:27,514
This was a man whose only crime was
to steal $5 from a local post office...

690
00:47:27,598 --> 00:47:29,558
...to feed his starving sister.

691
00:47:29,683 --> 00:47:33,353
He came to Alcatraz a petty criminal
who had never harmed...

692
00:47:33,478 --> 00:47:36,315
...or attempted to harm
another human being in his life.

693
00:47:36,356 --> 00:47:39,943
He came out of the dungeon a vicious,
barbaric, maniacal murderer.

694
00:47:40,360 --> 00:47:42,821
A man who had been put
into a psychological coma.

695
00:47:42,905 --> 00:47:45,407
Within an hour of coming out
of that hell hole...

696
00:47:45,532 --> 00:47:48,827
...he did what would've been unthinkable
to him three years before.

697
00:47:48,911 --> 00:47:50,162
Unthinkable!

698
00:47:50,370 --> 00:47:53,665
His only thought was murder!
His only instinct was murder.

699
00:47:53,874 --> 00:47:55,542
His first act was murder!

700
00:47:55,709 --> 00:47:59,338
He himself was a murder weapon,
but the hand that held that weapon...

701
00:47:59,421 --> 00:48:02,966
...and plunged it into the throat of McCain
belonged to someone else.

702
00:48:03,091 --> 00:48:05,344
l point to Associate Warden, Mr. Glenn...

703
00:48:05,427 --> 00:48:09,556
...Warden Humson and the institution
known as Alcatraz and say, ''l accuse! ''

704
00:48:09,765 --> 00:48:12,768
-Objection!
-l accuse them individually and collectively.

705
00:48:12,893 --> 00:48:16,146
l accuse Alcatraz of the torture
of Henri Young!

706
00:48:16,438 --> 00:48:19,358
-l accuse Alcatraz of McCain's murder!
-Come to order!

707
00:48:19,441 --> 00:48:22,152
Silence! This court will come to order!

708
00:48:25,113 --> 00:48:28,158
Henri Young is not going to be
the only defendant here!

709
00:48:28,408 --> 00:48:30,035
Alcatraz is on trial!

710
00:48:30,327 --> 00:48:33,038
<i>I will address your objection
tomorrow morning!</i>

711
00:48:33,580 --> 00:48:37,876
<i>Henri Young, on trial for his life, is seen
leaving the San Francisco courthouse...</i>

712
00:48:37,960 --> 00:48:42,214
<i>...followed by his young and now very
popular public defender, James Stamphill.</i>

713
00:48:42,297 --> 00:48:46,426
<i>Stamphill has accused the infamous Rock
of torture, using the tag line...</i>

714
00:48:46,635 --> 00:48:48,512
<i>...''crimes against humanity.''</i>

715
00:48:48,595 --> 00:48:51,890
<i>He has turned the once quiet trial
of a convict killing...</i>

716
00:48:52,057 --> 00:48:53,934
<i>...into a media circus.</i>

717
00:48:54,142 --> 00:48:56,562
ln most cases, they do get better.

718
00:48:58,313 --> 00:49:00,315
ln the case of Henri Young...

719
00:49:01,149 --> 00:49:03,318
...this happens not to be true.

720
00:49:03,610 --> 00:49:04,820
Young is a...

721
00:49:05,153 --> 00:49:06,363
...noisemaker.

722
00:49:06,655 --> 00:49:09,700
Some prisoners have a problem
when they're in...

723
00:49:10,993 --> 00:49:12,202
...solitary.

724
00:49:12,786 --> 00:49:15,914
All we do is try to discourage misconduct.

725
00:49:17,457 --> 00:49:20,752
<i>This is the first verbal attack
on the jewel of the prison system.</i>

726
00:49:20,836 --> 00:49:24,840
<i>This bastion that houses evil
opened in 1934.</i>

727
00:49:25,465 --> 00:49:27,467
<i>It brought gangsters like Capone...</i>

728
00:49:27,593 --> 00:49:32,347
<i>...Machine Gun Kelly and Henri Young
close to the magical city by the bay...</i>

729
00:49:32,681 --> 00:49:36,310
<i>...less than one half-mile
from the world-famous Fisherman's Wharf.</i>

730
00:49:36,518 --> 00:49:39,354
<i>We went to the streets
to find out public opinion.</i>

731
00:49:39,479 --> 00:49:42,482
You can't put a place on trial.
lt's a prison for prisoners.

732
00:49:42,608 --> 00:49:46,236
Now the murderers are accusing
the wardens of this and that.

733
00:49:46,320 --> 00:49:47,905
Doesn't make a lot of sense.

734
00:49:47,988 --> 00:49:50,073
Humson seems like a good guy.

735
00:49:50,199 --> 00:49:52,451
lf Alcatraz wasn't here l wouldn't live here.

736
00:49:52,534 --> 00:49:55,287
-You think it's too close?
-l think it's perfect.

737
00:49:55,495 --> 00:49:57,456
He's innocent until proven guilty.

738
00:49:57,581 --> 00:50:00,792
He'll get a fair trial, but, nonetheless,
he's a murderer.

739
00:50:01,043 --> 00:50:03,504
<i>This grizzly evidence bears mute witness...</i>

740
00:50:03,587 --> 00:50:06,757
<i>...to the brutal crime
perpetrated by Henri Young.</i>

741
00:50:07,341 --> 00:50:08,800
<i>Note the spoon.</i>

742
00:50:09,343 --> 00:50:11,345
<i>Can a prison be put on trial?</i>

743
00:50:11,470 --> 00:50:14,389
<i>Judge Clawson's ruling tomorrow
may clear the way...</i>

744
00:50:14,473 --> 00:50:16,558
<i>...to put Alcatraz on trial.</i>

745
00:50:16,892 --> 00:50:20,646
''The warden can be relied upon
to carry out the instructions...

746
00:50:20,854 --> 00:50:23,482
''...of the Bureau, that no brutality...

747
00:50:24,191 --> 00:50:26,568
''...or inhumanity shall be practiced.

748
00:50:26,902 --> 00:50:30,113
''Sustained food and medical attention
shall be given.''

749
00:50:30,280 --> 00:50:33,534
We have wholeheartedly followed
those instructions.

750
00:50:33,867 --> 00:50:34,868
Thank you.

751
00:50:35,202 --> 00:50:37,371
<i>So many opinions being expressed.</i>

752
00:50:37,579 --> 00:50:40,832
<i>We attempted to get a statement
from the recent Harvard graduate...</i>

753
00:50:40,916 --> 00:50:43,335
<i>...assigned to defend Henri Young.</i>

754
00:50:43,794 --> 00:50:46,964
Why don't we keep the trial
in the courtroom? Thank you.

755
00:50:48,090 --> 00:50:51,718
l would like to address a few words
to the counsel for the defense.

756
00:50:51,885 --> 00:50:54,513
Mr. Stamphill, you are hereby
put on notice...

757
00:50:54,721 --> 00:50:57,683
...that this court has no interest
in newspaper headlines...

758
00:50:57,766 --> 00:50:59,893
...and will not be swayed by them.

759
00:51:00,686 --> 00:51:05,524
l further admonish that counsel's attempts
to try this case in the press...

760
00:51:05,607 --> 00:51:09,361
...and not before this court,
will put him in the utmost peril.

761
00:51:11,572 --> 00:51:13,490
ls that clear, Mr. Stamphill?

762
00:51:13,740 --> 00:51:15,117
Yes, Your Honor.

763
00:51:15,450 --> 00:51:16,493
Good.

764
00:51:17,202 --> 00:51:19,079
Bailiff, approach the bench.

765
00:51:19,580 --> 00:51:23,083
Before l hand down my ruling
on Mr. McNeil's objection...

766
00:51:23,584 --> 00:51:27,212
...l'd like to address a few words
to the counsel for the defense.

767
00:51:27,296 --> 00:51:31,550
While l cannot give legal advice
and sit on the bench at the same time...

768
00:51:31,758 --> 00:51:35,429
...l will express grave concern
with the defense's strategy.

769
00:51:36,430 --> 00:51:39,516
Counselor, l strongly recommend
you walk a straight line...

770
00:51:39,641 --> 00:51:41,393
...in terms of your defense.

771
00:51:41,476 --> 00:51:46,023
Anything you state in this courtroom
will be evaluated not only by the jury...

772
00:51:46,273 --> 00:51:50,444
...but very closely scrutinized by myself.
ls that understood, Mr. Stamphill?

773
00:51:50,986 --> 00:51:52,112
Yes, Your Honor.

774
00:51:52,571 --> 00:51:53,697
Very well.

775
00:51:55,365 --> 00:51:57,409
Prosecution's objection is overruled.

776
00:51:58,327 --> 00:52:00,913
You may pursue your line of defense...

777
00:52:01,163 --> 00:52:03,415
...concerning the penitentiary at Alcatraz...

778
00:52:03,498 --> 00:52:07,044
...and l will rule on any objections
on a point-by-point basis.

779
00:52:07,294 --> 00:52:08,462
Exception.

780
00:52:08,629 --> 00:52:09,671
Noted.

781
00:52:09,796 --> 00:52:12,299
Mr. McNeil, you may call
your first witness.

782
00:52:12,508 --> 00:52:14,968
Prosecution calls Terrence Swenson.

783
00:52:16,470 --> 00:52:17,763
Terrence Swenson.

784
00:52:26,897 --> 00:52:29,858
Witness shall remain standing
until sworn in.

785
00:52:31,193 --> 00:52:32,945
Put your hand on the Bible.

786
00:52:33,028 --> 00:52:34,279
Cut it out.

787
00:52:34,363 --> 00:52:37,324
Do you swear to tell the truth
and nothing but the truth...

788
00:52:37,824 --> 00:52:39,284
...so help you God?

789
00:52:39,451 --> 00:52:40,786
So help me God.

790
00:52:40,869 --> 00:52:42,287
You may be seated.

791
00:52:43,330 --> 00:52:47,459
Mr. Swenson, as a guard at Alcatraz,
did you know Henri Young?

792
00:52:48,043 --> 00:52:48,794
Yes, sir.

793
00:52:48,877 --> 00:52:51,171
Could you point him out for us?

794
00:52:52,381 --> 00:52:54,424
That's him right over there, sir.

795
00:52:54,967 --> 00:52:56,593
Thank you, Mr. Whitney.

796
00:52:57,219 --> 00:52:58,136
Thank you.

797
00:52:58,178 --> 00:53:01,515
Now, on the morning of June 1 1, 1941,
where were you?

798
00:53:02,182 --> 00:53:04,560
l was on duty in the dining hall.

799
00:53:04,893 --> 00:53:06,436
Everything was normal.

800
00:53:06,854 --> 00:53:08,772
And l saw the defendant--

801
00:53:08,897 --> 00:53:09,940
Henri Young.

802
00:53:10,065 --> 00:53:11,400
That's correct.

803
00:53:11,733 --> 00:53:13,986
l saw him standing over Rufus McCain.

804
00:53:14,236 --> 00:53:16,280
He lifted up his chin and....

805
00:53:16,947 --> 00:53:18,991
-Excuse me, l'm nervous.
-lt's all right.

806
00:53:19,074 --> 00:53:21,577
And he plunged a metal object...

807
00:53:22,494 --> 00:53:24,621
...which l later learned was a spoon...

808
00:53:24,746 --> 00:53:26,415
...into McCain's throat.

809
00:53:27,207 --> 00:53:29,001
He then ripped it open.

810
00:53:30,419 --> 00:53:32,838
Did the defendant ever appear
to be ranting...

811
00:53:32,921 --> 00:53:33,881
...or raving?

812
00:53:34,006 --> 00:53:35,132
No, sir.

813
00:53:35,299 --> 00:53:37,801
Mr. McKeon, was he frothing
at the mouth?

814
00:53:38,177 --> 00:53:39,094
No, sir.

815
00:53:39,720 --> 00:53:43,140
Did he in any way give the impression
of one who was insane?

816
00:53:43,432 --> 00:53:46,560
Objection. This man is not
a qualified psychiatrist.

817
00:53:46,685 --> 00:53:47,728
Sustained.

818
00:53:47,936 --> 00:53:51,899
So, it appeared to you that it was a cool,
calculated and deliberate act?

819
00:53:52,274 --> 00:53:54,026
-Objection!
-Overruled.

820
00:53:54,234 --> 00:53:56,570
The witness may answer the question.

821
00:53:56,695 --> 00:53:59,823
Yes, sir. Young did it,
just as cool as a cucumber.

822
00:54:00,073 --> 00:54:01,200
Thank you.

823
00:54:01,491 --> 00:54:02,868
No further questions.

824
00:54:03,285 --> 00:54:06,246
This court will reconvene
after the holiday...

825
00:54:06,330 --> 00:54:07,956
...9:00 a.m., July 5.

826
00:54:08,123 --> 00:54:09,208
All rise.

827
00:54:09,333 --> 00:54:11,668
You should have played cards with me.

828
00:54:12,252 --> 00:54:13,462
Alcatraz.

829
00:54:13,962 --> 00:54:16,924
lt was built by the military
during the Civil War.

830
00:54:18,091 --> 00:54:21,470
ln May of '33, the War Department
abandoned the island.

831
00:54:22,471 --> 00:54:26,725
lt was leveled, all except for the lower
floor which is now used for storage.

832
00:54:27,100 --> 00:54:30,145
Note to myself:
Get access to the lower level...

833
00:54:30,270 --> 00:54:33,524
...because that's where the dungeons have
gotta be located.

834
00:54:33,649 --> 00:54:36,276
The only guard on record to be fired...

835
00:54:36,401 --> 00:54:40,030
...or dismissed during Henri's solitary time
was Derek Simpson.

836
00:54:40,572 --> 00:54:42,032
Locate Simpson.

837
00:54:42,324 --> 00:54:45,702
The prison opened in June of '34
under Warden Humson.

838
00:54:46,578 --> 00:54:49,540
He insisted on a high level
of guards to prisoners.

839
00:54:49,581 --> 00:54:51,583
Glenn was the first appointee.

840
00:54:53,335 --> 00:54:54,461
Mr. Henkin.

841
00:54:54,795 --> 00:54:57,256
Two things: First of all, you work for me.

842
00:54:57,464 --> 00:54:58,924
Let me finish!

843
00:55:00,008 --> 00:55:03,554
You work for me, which means
when l call you, you drop everything.

844
00:55:03,679 --> 00:55:06,390
Return my call or you will cease
to work for me.

845
00:55:06,682 --> 00:55:08,976
l don't care if you're with Rita Hayworth!

846
00:55:09,351 --> 00:55:10,435
Understand?

847
00:55:10,769 --> 00:55:12,187
-Yes, sir.
-Good.

848
00:55:15,315 --> 00:55:17,609
What the hell are you doing with this trial?

849
00:55:17,693 --> 00:55:18,944
Defending my client.

850
00:55:19,027 --> 00:55:21,572
Then why don't you defend him
for Christ's sake?

851
00:55:21,655 --> 00:55:24,908
Try to knock down the charges
as a crime of passion or figure out...

852
00:55:24,992 --> 00:55:27,452
...how you'll cross-examine
the witnesses...

853
00:55:27,536 --> 00:55:32,165
...instead of this ''psychological coma'' crap
that doesn't mean anything in court!

854
00:55:32,374 --> 00:55:34,543
l think it does. As long as it's my case--

855
00:55:34,626 --> 00:55:39,089
Fair enough. l tried to talk reasonably
to you, but you're not going for it, so...

856
00:55:39,840 --> 00:55:42,801
...you're not handling this case anymore.
lt's done.

857
00:55:43,010 --> 00:55:44,303
Mr. Henkin...

858
00:55:45,220 --> 00:55:48,974
...they're printing my opening statement
in 250 newspapers across the country.

859
00:55:49,057 --> 00:55:52,477
lf you want me off the case because
you're afraid of taking on Alcatraz...

860
00:55:52,603 --> 00:55:54,146
...that's your choice.

861
00:55:54,229 --> 00:55:57,774
But l'll just go to Jerry Hoolihan
and tell my side of the story.

862
00:55:58,400 --> 00:56:01,945
lf you want to play hardball, sir,
l'll play hardball too.

863
00:56:07,910 --> 00:56:09,620
l'm trying to be your friend.

864
00:56:10,412 --> 00:56:12,414
You know who the warden of Alcatraz is?

865
00:56:12,539 --> 00:56:16,835
He's the most highly respected warden
in the US dealing with hardened criminals.

866
00:56:17,836 --> 00:56:20,506
lf you try to make Humson
look like a Nazi...

867
00:56:21,048 --> 00:56:23,217
...they will eat you for breakfast.

868
00:56:32,226 --> 00:56:35,646
You'll die if l can't get corroboration
about what goes on over there.

869
00:56:35,771 --> 00:56:38,732
l need names! Names of men
who'll come and testify.

870
00:56:39,149 --> 00:56:42,277
What made you think
these men will come and testify?

871
00:56:42,402 --> 00:56:45,072
Maybe you got some friends
you don't know about.

872
00:56:45,781 --> 00:56:49,201
-You want to play cards?
-l'll make them testify with a court order!

873
00:56:49,284 --> 00:56:52,371
What about when they're back
on the Rock with Mr. Glenn?

874
00:56:52,538 --> 00:56:54,373
They'll kill them, that's what.

875
00:56:54,456 --> 00:56:57,501
This is our only chance.
We're talking about your life.

876
00:56:57,626 --> 00:57:01,547
For a smart guy, you're awfully slow.
l'm already dead. l told you that.

877
00:57:01,797 --> 00:57:04,049
You can't change Alcatraz.

878
00:57:04,466 --> 00:57:05,634
lt just is.

879
00:57:05,717 --> 00:57:07,094
So why fight it?

880
00:57:07,261 --> 00:57:11,265
You stand in court preaching. l don't
even know what you're talking about.

881
00:57:11,431 --> 00:57:13,642
Justice. l'm talking about justice.

882
00:57:13,976 --> 00:57:16,854
l killed him, they saw it,
they're going to kill me.

883
00:57:16,895 --> 00:57:18,772
Nothing you say will change that.

884
00:57:18,856 --> 00:57:21,358
So l don't see what you're
so excited about.

885
00:57:21,650 --> 00:57:25,487
This trial doesn't interest you at all?
You don't care about it a bit?

886
00:57:26,613 --> 00:57:29,616
You look like you're having
a good time, so....

887
00:57:30,325 --> 00:57:31,910
No, l don't care.

888
00:57:32,327 --> 00:57:36,373
Main thing is, l got a friend my age
to talk to until they gas me.

889
00:57:37,165 --> 00:57:41,628
l'm not your friend, l'm your attorney.
l'm trying to save your life. Guard!

890
00:57:41,920 --> 00:57:44,339
You know, l have a sister, but...

891
00:57:45,340 --> 00:57:47,885
...l ain't seen her since they put me in jail.

892
00:57:47,968 --> 00:57:50,137
l got nothing. l got nobody.

893
00:57:50,345 --> 00:57:53,015
l don't need a lawyer. l need a friend.

894
00:57:53,682 --> 00:57:58,228
You're doing all this to prove something
to a guy named Darryl, not for me.

895
00:57:58,854 --> 00:58:00,981
You want to do something for me?

896
00:58:01,857 --> 00:58:03,442
Let's play cards.

897
00:58:06,361 --> 00:58:08,739
Go ahead and play cards.
l got a case to try.

898
00:58:08,780 --> 00:58:11,283
Hold it, Jim. Where are you going?

899
00:58:11,950 --> 00:58:13,493
Where are you going?

900
00:58:23,128 --> 00:58:26,173
<i>I'm Henri Young's attorney.
I'd like to ask you a few questions.</i>

901
00:58:26,381 --> 00:58:30,135
<i>I'm going to call prisoners to the stand
to testify about life on Alcatraz.</i>

902
00:58:30,219 --> 00:58:31,970
<i>Where are the dungeons?</i>

903
00:58:32,054 --> 00:58:34,306
<i>What is solitary time
in those dungeons like?</i>

904
00:58:34,389 --> 00:58:36,558
<i>I want the jury to know and understand.</i>

905
00:58:36,683 --> 00:58:39,645
<i>You tell them to get caught
robbing a bank. They'll find out.</i>

906
00:58:40,521 --> 00:58:42,105
l'm done talking.

907
00:58:56,745 --> 00:58:57,788
Mr. Murphy...

908
00:58:57,913 --> 00:59:02,376
...if we can get decent treatment for you,
it makes it possible for everyone.

909
00:59:02,584 --> 00:59:07,047
lf we ignore cruelty in one place,
it makes it more acceptable everywhere.

910
00:59:07,381 --> 00:59:09,258
l ain't gonna do shit for you.

911
00:59:09,925 --> 00:59:12,678
You can't get me no good time
knocked off.

912
00:59:12,928 --> 00:59:14,805
You can't get me no privileges.

913
00:59:14,847 --> 00:59:18,809
You can't even get me seconds at dessert.
lf l testify for anybody...

914
00:59:19,017 --> 00:59:22,145
...l testify for the DA.
He's got some juice here.

915
00:59:26,650 --> 00:59:30,028
<i>Mr. Baker, could you tell me anything
about Henri Young?</i>

916
00:59:30,279 --> 00:59:31,905
Don't know Henri Young.

917
00:59:33,031 --> 00:59:35,534
Could you tell us anything
about Mr. Glenn?

918
00:59:37,870 --> 00:59:39,872
Warden Glenn has always been
good to me.

919
00:59:42,958 --> 00:59:45,210
Have you ever been in the dungeons?

920
00:59:45,752 --> 00:59:48,130
l don't know nothing about no dungeons.

921
00:59:48,797 --> 00:59:50,215
That's all, ma'am.

922
00:59:50,632 --> 00:59:52,092
l gotta go now.

923
00:59:56,221 --> 00:59:57,472
Fuck you.

924
00:59:58,140 --> 01:00:01,059
Did Mr. Glenn tell you
not to cooperate with me?

925
01:00:01,560 --> 01:00:02,769
Fuck you.

926
01:00:02,978 --> 01:00:05,230
Where are the dungeons located?

927
01:00:05,606 --> 01:00:07,816
Don't take my fucking picture!

928
01:00:12,196 --> 01:00:15,032
You know l can get
a writ of habeas corpus testificandum...

929
01:00:15,073 --> 01:00:17,701
...and force you to come
and testify in court?

930
01:00:17,826 --> 01:00:19,077
Fuck you!

931
01:00:20,579 --> 01:00:22,748
Thank you very much for your time.

932
01:00:22,873 --> 01:00:24,416
Don't mention it.

933
01:00:26,251 --> 01:00:28,045
And you, sweetheart....

934
01:00:28,504 --> 01:00:30,255
l'd like to fuck you.

935
01:00:47,105 --> 01:00:49,525
<i>I hope your day has been fruitful.</i>

936
01:00:50,984 --> 01:00:54,655
l don't see your photographer.
ls he still taking pictures?

937
01:00:54,863 --> 01:00:56,365
He's trying to.

938
01:00:56,949 --> 01:00:59,451
We're not receiving a great deal
of cooperation.

939
01:00:59,535 --> 01:01:03,205
lt almost seems as though someone told
the prisoners not to talk to us.

940
01:01:03,288 --> 01:01:04,873
There's no conspiracy.

941
01:01:05,207 --> 01:01:06,667
No one talked to them.

942
01:01:06,792 --> 01:01:09,920
Maybe it's because they are
dangerous people who belong here...

943
01:01:10,003 --> 01:01:12,047
...with no interest in you or your case.

944
01:01:12,130 --> 01:01:15,259
-l'd like to see the dungeons.
-l'm sorry? Dungeons?

945
01:01:15,968 --> 01:01:18,220
The old citadel, the sub-level of the prison.

946
01:01:18,303 --> 01:01:20,180
That's mostly storage...

947
01:01:20,264 --> 01:01:22,140
...a few solitary cells.

948
01:01:22,182 --> 01:01:23,100
No dungeons.

949
01:01:23,141 --> 01:01:26,395
l would like to see
the solitary-confinement cells.

950
01:01:26,562 --> 01:01:29,106
l would love to show those cells to you,
but l can't.

951
01:01:29,189 --> 01:01:33,694
lt's an insurance risk to visitors during a
riot. lf you're there, we can't protect you.

952
01:01:33,819 --> 01:01:35,529
Thank you for your concern.

953
01:01:35,988 --> 01:01:38,282
l could show you the exercise yard.

954
01:01:40,409 --> 01:01:41,785
You have papers.

955
01:01:42,202 --> 01:01:45,122
l have papers, so you can cut
the good-guy act.

956
01:01:46,498 --> 01:01:49,168
l do consider myself
as one of the good guys...

957
01:01:49,334 --> 01:01:51,503
...and perhaps more than you...

958
01:01:51,795 --> 01:01:53,839
...l know what the bad guys are like.

959
01:01:53,964 --> 01:01:56,008
l'd like to read them. Please.

960
01:01:57,342 --> 01:01:58,468
Thank you.

961
01:02:00,470 --> 01:02:01,805
That's a court order...

962
01:02:01,889 --> 01:02:05,434
<i>...instructing you to permit us access
to the solitary-confinement cells.</i>

963
01:02:05,517 --> 01:02:08,604
<i>And to allow the photographer
to take pictures of the same...</i>

964
01:02:08,729 --> 01:02:11,732
<i>...to be used as exhibits in the trial
of The People vs. Young.</i>

965
01:02:11,857 --> 01:02:14,067
<i>You are also instructed
to hand over to us...</i>

966
01:02:14,193 --> 01:02:17,696
<i>...the complete medical
and disciplinary files as to therein.</i>

967
01:02:18,030 --> 01:02:19,698
<i>If you refuse to do so...</i>

968
01:02:19,823 --> 01:02:22,868
<i>...you'll have to appear in court
and show just cause.</i>

969
01:02:29,583 --> 01:02:32,169
Why don't you take Miss McCasslin
out for some air?

970
01:02:32,252 --> 01:02:34,046
l was told not to leave you alone.

971
01:02:34,171 --> 01:02:38,342
l don't care. You may be used to
these conditions but obviously she's not.

972
01:02:39,259 --> 01:02:43,722
We've been searched. Take her outside,
or we'll discuss this with Mr. Glenn.

973
01:02:43,847 --> 01:02:45,182
All right.

974
01:02:45,390 --> 01:02:46,725
No more photos.

975
01:02:47,893 --> 01:02:49,102
You all right?

976
01:02:49,603 --> 01:02:50,604
Thanks.

977
01:02:50,812 --> 01:02:52,439
l just need some air.

978
01:03:15,629 --> 01:03:16,797
My God!

979
01:03:38,110 --> 01:03:41,488
My name's James Stamphill.
l'm Henri Young's attorney.

980
01:03:41,572 --> 01:03:44,116
l can force them to let you out
so you can testify...

981
01:03:44,241 --> 01:03:46,201
<i>...in San Francisco in a court of law.</i>

982
01:03:46,285 --> 01:03:50,330
<i>You just have to give me your name.
I promise I will do what I said for you.</i>

983
01:04:05,137 --> 01:04:07,598
James, she's okay. Just needed some air.

984
01:04:11,476 --> 01:04:12,519
Can we go now?

985
01:04:12,644 --> 01:04:14,104
Feeling any better?

986
01:04:15,480 --> 01:04:17,149
l guess l'll make it.

987
01:04:20,652 --> 01:04:23,197
-Did you get anything?
-l got three names.

988
01:04:24,823 --> 01:04:25,866
Let's go.

989
01:04:27,451 --> 01:04:30,245
<i>Where did Stamphill get
the three names on this list?</i>

990
01:04:33,832 --> 01:04:35,209
l don't know.

991
01:04:35,292 --> 01:04:39,755
Can you trust these cons? They're smart
enough to look after their own interests.

992
01:04:39,838 --> 01:04:41,006
They told Glenn...

993
01:04:41,131 --> 01:04:45,385
<i>...James said he'd get them out of solitary
if they would testify for the defense...</i>

994
01:04:45,469 --> 01:04:47,471
<i>-...and lie on the stand!
- That's a lie.</i>

995
01:04:47,596 --> 01:04:51,934
<i>-He wanted to find one convict willing--
-Jesus, this is goddamn bribery.</i>

996
01:04:51,975 --> 01:04:55,938
<i>It's prejudicing a witness.
You could get disbarred. It's gone too far.</i>

997
01:04:56,104 --> 01:04:58,357
<i>Fire him. I don't care how you do it.</i>

998
01:04:58,482 --> 01:05:00,859
Why do you have to make it be like this?

999
01:05:00,984 --> 01:05:03,779
Henri Young's my client.
lt's my job to defend him !

1000
01:05:03,862 --> 01:05:04,821
Not anymore.

1001
01:05:04,947 --> 01:05:05,906
What?

1002
01:05:05,989 --> 01:05:08,951
He's been notified that Henkin
wants you off the case.

1003
01:05:09,326 --> 01:05:10,786
Henri will never go for it.

1004
01:05:10,827 --> 01:05:13,747
-He did. He's been assigned a new lawyer.
-Who?

1005
01:05:15,374 --> 01:05:16,333
Me.

1006
01:05:18,544 --> 01:05:19,127
Me.

1007
01:05:19,253 --> 01:05:23,173
Henkin assigned me to the case.
l could take it or be fired. l had no choice.

1008
01:05:23,549 --> 01:05:25,133
You stabbed me in the back?

1009
01:05:25,217 --> 01:05:28,136
l'm not stabbing you!
l'm trying to save your job and mine!

1010
01:05:28,178 --> 01:05:32,099
What about Henri's life?
lsn't that more important than profit?

1011
01:05:32,182 --> 01:05:34,977
l don't have a brother who's a partner
in a big law firm.

1012
01:05:35,060 --> 01:05:39,106
There aren't any other jobs
waiting out there for a woman attorney.

1013
01:05:39,189 --> 01:05:41,900
The only option l had was to do
what he told me to do.

1014
01:05:42,025 --> 01:05:43,485
What could l have done?

1015
01:05:43,527 --> 01:05:44,987
l'll see you.

1016
01:06:05,883 --> 01:06:08,510
What we need to do is establish exactly....

1017
01:06:08,635 --> 01:06:11,680
We have a lot of work to get to today,
if you don't mind.

1018
01:06:11,763 --> 01:06:12,848
Stop that.

1019
01:06:13,223 --> 01:06:15,767
Jesus Christ, all l was doing was looking.

1020
01:06:16,185 --> 01:06:17,811
l want to set you straight--

1021
01:06:17,895 --> 01:06:20,689
You set me straight
the minute you walked in.

1022
01:06:21,023 --> 01:06:23,442
-Mr. Young--
-Please, call me Henri. Please.

1023
01:06:23,525 --> 01:06:27,696
Mr. Young, l am not here to satisfy
any sexual fantasies that you may have.

1024
01:06:30,949 --> 01:06:31,909
You're not?

1025
01:06:32,743 --> 01:06:34,620
No, l'm your attorney.

1026
01:06:34,912 --> 01:06:36,622
They're gonna kill me anyway.

1027
01:06:37,497 --> 01:06:41,251
You won't do me any good as an attorney.
You may as well be good for something.

1028
01:06:41,376 --> 01:06:44,880
-Mr. Young, l can't--
-Please, call me Henri, can't you?

1029
01:06:45,714 --> 01:06:48,425
l just want to hear a lady call me Henri.

1030
01:06:48,550 --> 01:06:49,927
Can't you, please?

1031
01:06:50,469 --> 01:06:51,720
Just once.

1032
01:06:52,554 --> 01:06:53,597
Please.

1033
01:06:55,974 --> 01:06:57,601
Henri, listen, we have so--

1034
01:06:57,726 --> 01:07:00,187
Yeah, yeah. That's it. That's it.

1035
01:07:02,564 --> 01:07:04,650
l'm gonna touch you just a little bit.

1036
01:07:04,942 --> 01:07:05,901
Just a little.

1037
01:07:06,026 --> 01:07:07,486
Are you crazy?

1038
01:07:07,945 --> 01:07:10,447
Yeah, sure. lt won't hurt you
to let me touch you.

1039
01:07:10,822 --> 01:07:13,742
Don't make me call the guard.
We're running late on....

1040
01:07:14,576 --> 01:07:15,536
Stop that.

1041
01:07:17,329 --> 01:07:18,247
Stop.

1042
01:07:18,413 --> 01:07:20,249
Stop that! Stop that!

1043
01:07:20,499 --> 01:07:22,751
l'm not touching you. l'm touching me.

1044
01:07:24,294 --> 01:07:25,420
Guard!

1045
01:07:29,591 --> 01:07:31,009
You have a problem?

1046
01:07:34,012 --> 01:07:35,556
Did he do anything?

1047
01:07:38,517 --> 01:07:39,518
No.

1048
01:07:39,893 --> 01:07:41,395
Let me know if he does.

1049
01:07:41,478 --> 01:07:43,313
No, l'd like to leave now.

1050
01:08:00,956 --> 01:08:03,250
-He wants to see you in there.
-What?

1051
01:08:05,544 --> 01:08:07,462
He wants to see you in there.

1052
01:08:36,909 --> 01:08:39,870
So, why'd you want to meet here?
Neutral territory?

1053
01:08:43,832 --> 01:08:45,876
Want to be my lawyer again?

1054
01:08:48,504 --> 01:08:50,214
What happened to the other one?

1055
01:08:50,339 --> 01:08:52,382
l don't know if l want her.

1056
01:08:52,674 --> 01:08:54,593
Since l had her, l mean.

1057
01:08:56,345 --> 01:08:57,888
She was good, though.

1058
01:08:58,430 --> 01:09:01,892
She was everything l wanted
my first experience to be.

1059
01:09:02,100 --> 01:09:04,561
l was just talking and she came over.

1060
01:09:04,645 --> 01:09:07,856
-She started touching me--
-That's great. That's great.

1061
01:09:12,277 --> 01:09:14,363
Jim, l'm just playing a joke on you.

1062
01:09:17,908 --> 01:09:19,868
l know she was your girlfriend.

1063
01:09:20,244 --> 01:09:23,330
l remember from the smell of the perfume
on your jacket.

1064
01:09:28,961 --> 01:09:30,295
So, Lawyer...

1065
01:09:32,130 --> 01:09:33,841
...you want to come back?

1066
01:09:35,133 --> 01:09:36,260
l resigned.

1067
01:09:38,220 --> 01:09:41,056
l guess that means
l'm in private practice now.

1068
01:09:42,432 --> 01:09:44,142
l could've had her though.

1069
01:09:45,477 --> 01:09:46,603
Of course...

1070
01:09:47,437 --> 01:09:49,398
...she don't play cards.

1071
01:09:57,072 --> 01:09:59,074
<i>After I got arrested, they...</i>

1072
01:09:59,533 --> 01:10:00,993
<i>...took my sister away.</i>

1073
01:10:01,827 --> 01:10:02,870
<i>They...</i>

1074
01:10:03,412 --> 01:10:06,081
<i>...put her in a home or orphanage and...</i>

1075
01:10:07,082 --> 01:10:08,542
<i>...I don't know....</i>

1076
01:10:09,710 --> 01:10:12,921
<i>I don't know what happened to her.
Never saw her again.</i>

1077
01:10:13,005 --> 01:10:15,174
<i>My parents died when I was 7.</i>

1078
01:10:15,465 --> 01:10:19,761
<i>It was just me and my brother, and he
didn't know anything about raising a child.</i>

1079
01:10:20,429 --> 01:10:22,598
<i>He sent me off to boarding school.</i>

1080
01:10:22,681 --> 01:10:25,017
<i>I did get to come home on holidays.</i>

1081
01:10:26,435 --> 01:10:28,312
He put me through law school...

1082
01:10:28,395 --> 01:10:31,607
