1209
01:18:35,424 --> 01:18:37,259
lt's gonna cost extra, you know.

1210
01:18:38,093 --> 01:18:40,012
Just do what you have to do.

1211
01:19:14,296 --> 01:19:15,422
l can't.

1212
01:19:17,716 --> 01:19:18,884
l'm sorry.

1213
01:19:23,805 --> 01:19:24,765
l can't.

1214
01:19:35,234 --> 01:19:37,194
Hey, we only had a few minutes.

1215
01:19:38,070 --> 01:19:40,656
You got another guy in the room.
That's okay.

1216
01:19:51,750 --> 01:19:52,960
Shh, baby.

1217
01:19:58,173 --> 01:20:02,010
Your Honor, the defense calls
Associate Warden, Mr. Milton Glenn.

1218
01:20:18,151 --> 01:20:21,321
Do you swear to tell the truth
and nothing but the truth?

1219
01:20:21,405 --> 01:20:23,532
-So help me God.
-You may be seated.

1220
01:20:34,251 --> 01:20:38,839
As associate warden, you are responsible
for the day-to-day running of the prison?

1221
01:20:39,006 --> 01:20:40,132
You could say that.

1222
01:20:40,257 --> 01:20:42,843
Then you must be familiar
with the dungeons.

1223
01:20:43,385 --> 01:20:44,970
l'm sure you've heard of them.

1224
01:20:45,095 --> 01:20:47,848
Some prisoners refer
to the lower levels as dungeons.

1225
01:20:48,182 --> 01:20:51,143
They refer to bread and water
as piss and punk.

1226
01:20:51,894 --> 01:20:55,314
The dictionary definition of a dungeon is:
''A close, dark prison...

1227
01:20:55,439 --> 01:20:57,900
''...or vault, commonly underground.''

1228
01:20:58,609 --> 01:21:02,529
The walls of those cells are 6 feet by 9,
and the roof 5 to 6 feet tall.

1229
01:21:02,613 --> 01:21:05,240
-Would you call that close?
-ln my opinion, no.

1230
01:21:05,449 --> 01:21:08,410
-Are there any light fixtures?
-No, but there aren't any books.

1231
01:21:08,535 --> 01:21:09,494
Your Honor...

1232
01:21:10,037 --> 01:21:13,790
...the defense offers these photographs
as defense exhibits B, C, D, E and F.

1233
01:21:13,916 --> 01:21:17,127
How much light is in these cells
with no window and the door closed?

1234
01:21:17,252 --> 01:21:20,339
-Not much.
-How long was Henri held in such a cell?

1235
01:21:20,714 --> 01:21:22,007
l don't know exactly.

1236
01:21:22,132 --> 01:21:25,385
Three years and two months!
l have the records, if you'd like to see.

1237
01:21:25,802 --> 01:21:28,138
-That sounds right.
-Three years and two months.

1238
01:21:28,222 --> 01:21:32,100
ln that time, how often was Henri Young
allowed outside for exercise?

1239
01:21:32,392 --> 01:21:36,688
Mr. Stamphill, l do not believe that
the exercise time of an inmate is relevant.

1240
01:21:36,897 --> 01:21:38,357
l do. Answer the question.

1241
01:21:38,440 --> 01:21:40,275
-Objection!
-Objection overruled!

1242
01:21:40,359 --> 01:21:42,152
Henri Young tried to escape.

1243
01:21:42,277 --> 01:21:45,697
When a criminal escapes from prison,
he doesn't go job-hunting.

1244
01:21:45,781 --> 01:21:49,368
He robs somebody or kills somebody.
We do all we can to discourage escape.

1245
01:21:49,493 --> 01:21:53,413
ln three years and two months, how often
was Henri allowed outside for exercise?

1246
01:21:53,997 --> 01:21:56,625
-Men sentenced to Alcatraz--
-Answer the question!

1247
01:21:56,750 --> 01:22:00,045
How often was he allowed
outside for exercise?

1248
01:22:00,212 --> 01:22:03,382
-Objection! He's badgering the witness.
-Objection overruled.

1249
01:22:03,507 --> 01:22:05,926
Mr. Glenn, you will answer that question.

1250
01:22:07,261 --> 01:22:08,971
Young man, l do not recall.

1251
01:22:09,680 --> 01:22:10,973
You don't know?

1252
01:22:11,098 --> 01:22:15,143
Surely a half hour a year isn't
too difficult to recall, now, is it?

1253
01:22:16,061 --> 01:22:18,522
-There is no place in my court for sarcasm.
-Sorry.

1254
01:22:18,605 --> 01:22:21,108
l have here a list with 32 names on it.

1255
01:22:21,275 --> 01:22:25,237
These are men who were prisoners
at Alcatraz during your tenure. Correct?

1256
01:22:25,362 --> 01:22:27,573
l can't remember the name
of every prisoner.

1257
01:22:27,698 --> 01:22:31,660
l have committal papers with your
signature as well as the late Dr. Kiley's.

1258
01:22:31,785 --> 01:22:33,704
This is defense exhibit G.

1259
01:22:34,496 --> 01:22:38,876
All these men were taken off Alcatraz in
straitjackets and put in mental institutions.

1260
01:22:38,959 --> 01:22:40,544
-ls that correct?
-Objection!

1261
01:22:40,669 --> 01:22:42,129
The question is immaterial.

1262
01:22:42,212 --> 01:22:46,925
lmmaterial? Your Honor, l'm saying in lay
terms that Alcatraz drives people insane.

1263
01:22:47,050 --> 01:22:52,014
lt has already done so in 32 instances.
lf this is not true, the witness can say so.

1264
01:22:52,097 --> 01:22:54,266
lf it is true, it is most material...

1265
01:22:54,391 --> 01:22:57,311
...and the jury ought to be privy
to that knowledge.

1266
01:22:57,477 --> 01:22:58,937
Objection overruled.

1267
01:22:59,021 --> 01:23:00,022
Thank you.

1268
01:23:00,147 --> 01:23:01,106
Now...

1269
01:23:01,315 --> 01:23:05,611
...is it not true that these men were taken
off Alcatraz in straightjackets...

1270
01:23:05,903 --> 01:23:10,199
...and placed in mental institutions
and you and Dr. Kiley signed the papers?

1271
01:23:10,282 --> 01:23:11,033
True.

1272
01:23:11,158 --> 01:23:13,827
ls it not also true that of these 32 men...

1273
01:23:13,994 --> 01:23:17,497
...28 of them had never before set foot
inside a mental institution?

1274
01:23:17,581 --> 01:23:20,125
-l don't know.
-Would you like to see the records?

1275
01:23:20,250 --> 01:23:22,044
l'll take your word for it.

1276
01:23:22,252 --> 01:23:25,005
Here are men who came to Alcatraz
legally sane...

1277
01:23:25,339 --> 01:23:29,051
...were subjected to the conditions
of Alcatraz, then deemed to be insane.

1278
01:23:29,134 --> 01:23:30,219
ls that correct?

1279
01:23:30,302 --> 01:23:33,055
Yes, but you can't say
that one causes the other.

1280
01:23:33,263 --> 01:23:36,892
lnsanity's not a virus, is it?
lt's not something we're all going to catch.

1281
01:23:37,017 --> 01:23:39,645
Objection, the witness is not
a psychiatrist!

1282
01:23:39,770 --> 01:23:41,230
Objection sustained.

1283
01:23:41,563 --> 01:23:42,731
Mr. Stamphill...

1284
01:23:42,814 --> 01:23:46,026
...confine your questions to areas
of Mr. Glenn's expertise.

1285
01:23:46,109 --> 01:23:49,738
Very well, Mr. Glenn's expertise!
Have you ever beaten a prisoner?

1286
01:23:49,988 --> 01:23:51,240
No, that's illegal.

1287
01:23:51,323 --> 01:23:53,116
-Not even when provoked?
-No!

1288
01:23:53,575 --> 01:23:56,537
You've never hit, kicked,
used a blackjack or a razor?

1289
01:23:56,620 --> 01:23:59,206
You've never punched a prisoner
in your entire career?

1290
01:23:59,289 --> 01:24:01,291
-Objection, Your Honor!
-Sustained.

1291
01:24:01,333 --> 01:24:03,460
Confine yourself to one question at a time.

1292
01:24:03,585 --> 01:24:08,048
ls it not true you ordered two guards to
throw Henri down a steel flight of stairs?

1293
01:24:08,131 --> 01:24:10,467
That you smashed his face
with a blackjack?

1294
01:24:10,592 --> 01:24:14,429
That you took a straight razor, sliced open
his ankle, hobbling him for life?

1295
01:24:14,471 --> 01:24:15,973
Answer the question!

1296
01:24:16,014 --> 01:24:16,807
Objection!

1297
01:24:16,932 --> 01:24:20,769
-He testified he didn't beat any prisoners.
-He's testified to a lot of things.

1298
01:24:20,894 --> 01:24:24,106
Are you aware that, in a federal court
system, perjury is a crime?

1299
01:24:24,231 --> 01:24:26,400
-You could go to jail!
-Young is on trial!

1300
01:24:26,483 --> 01:24:30,445
Mind you, young man, that Henri Young
is the one on trial here, not me!

1301
01:24:30,612 --> 01:24:33,615
l am a public servant!
l am not the bad guy!

1302
01:24:33,782 --> 01:24:37,661
l will not be treated the same way as this,
this lying, murdering...

1303
01:24:37,828 --> 01:24:39,162
...two-time loser!

1304
01:24:39,496 --> 01:24:40,998
Silence, Mr. Glenn!

1305
01:24:41,164 --> 01:24:45,210
Mr. Stamphill, you are perilously close
to contempt of this court!

1306
01:24:46,253 --> 01:24:49,131
You will proceed with caution!
ls that understood?

1307
01:24:51,758 --> 01:24:53,260
Temper, temper.

1308
01:24:56,513 --> 01:24:58,807
Would you care to withdraw
any testimony?

1309
01:24:58,932 --> 01:25:02,477
You wouldn't want somebody to testify
to the contrary, would you?

1310
01:25:03,020 --> 01:25:05,606
No. l would not withdraw any testimony...

1311
01:25:06,190 --> 01:25:08,358
...no matter what Henri Young
has told you.

1312
01:25:08,650 --> 01:25:11,820
l'm not talking about Henri Young.
Who would believe him?

1313
01:25:13,155 --> 01:25:16,074
Mr. Simpson, did you ever beat
this man, Henri Young?

1314
01:25:16,158 --> 01:25:18,118
Objection! This has no bearing.

1315
01:25:18,202 --> 01:25:21,663
No bearing? Beatings have a bearing
on a man's state of mind.

1316
01:25:21,872 --> 01:25:24,124
So does three years of darkness.

1317
01:25:24,291 --> 01:25:28,295
Do we need to be psychologists to know
that? You know that. l know you do.

1318
01:25:28,378 --> 01:25:29,630
Objection overruled.

1319
01:25:29,713 --> 01:25:31,298
Thank you, Your Honor.

1320
01:25:31,965 --> 01:25:34,927
<i>Did you ever beat Henri Young
with a blackjack?</i>

1321
01:25:35,177 --> 01:25:35,969
<i>Yes.</i>

1322
01:25:36,053 --> 01:25:39,014
<i>Did you ever throw Henri Young
down a steel flight of stairs?</i>

1323
01:25:39,056 --> 01:25:39,890
<i>Yes, I did.</i>

1324
01:25:40,015 --> 01:25:42,017
<i>-You were ordered to do this?
-Yes, sir.</i>

1325
01:25:42,142 --> 01:25:43,685
<i>Tell us the name of the man...</i>

1326
01:25:43,810 --> 01:25:46,688
...who was your superior who ordered you
to do these things.

1327
01:25:46,772 --> 01:25:47,856
Mr. Glenn.

1328
01:25:47,981 --> 01:25:50,651
You never went to Warden Humson
about these matters?

1329
01:25:50,734 --> 01:25:51,568
No, sir.

1330
01:25:51,693 --> 01:25:55,864
Thank you very much. l won't ask where
you got your bruises. l already know.

1331
01:25:56,490 --> 01:25:59,493
The prosecution would like to mark
for identification...

1332
01:25:59,576 --> 01:26:02,204
...the employment records
of Mr. Derek Simpson.

1333
01:26:02,329 --> 01:26:03,789
Do you recall...

1334
01:26:03,997 --> 01:26:07,084
...being suspended on November 4, 1936...

1335
01:26:07,417 --> 01:26:09,920
...and again on July 6, 1937?

1336
01:26:11,004 --> 01:26:11,880
Yeah.

1337
01:26:12,005 --> 01:26:13,173
Speak up.

1338
01:26:14,007 --> 01:26:15,008
Yes.

1339
01:26:15,843 --> 01:26:20,472
ls it not a fact you were fired from your job
as a guard because you are a drunk?

1340
01:26:20,722 --> 01:26:22,516
-Objection!
-That's not true!

1341
01:26:22,599 --> 01:26:23,392
Objection!

1342
01:26:23,517 --> 01:26:24,977
-Overruled.
-Mr. Glenn...

1343
01:26:25,060 --> 01:26:27,187
...wouldn't tolerate this in a prison.

1344
01:26:27,271 --> 01:26:29,898
lsn't it true, having cost you your job...

1345
01:26:30,107 --> 01:26:33,110
...you would say anything
to get even with Mr. Glenn?

1346
01:26:33,861 --> 01:26:36,905
<i>The jury will disregard
Mr. Simpson's testimony.</i>

1347
01:26:38,448 --> 01:26:41,910
Good afternoon, Mr. Stamphill,
is everything all right?

1348
01:26:53,255 --> 01:26:55,090
-Son of a bitch!
-What happened?

1349
01:26:55,174 --> 01:26:56,925
You know exactly! You set me up!

1350
01:26:57,050 --> 01:26:58,218
What are you talking about?

1351
01:26:58,302 --> 01:27:00,304
You took Simpson's picture
off of my desk!

1352
01:27:00,429 --> 01:27:03,557
They never would've known
to tear him down if you hadn't told them !

1353
01:27:03,640 --> 01:27:05,726
Are you going to hit me now?

1354
01:27:05,976 --> 01:27:07,060
Go ahead.

1355
01:27:07,477 --> 01:27:10,314
lt's about time you grew up
and were a man.

1356
01:27:15,277 --> 01:27:16,695
You're my brother.

1357
01:27:17,487 --> 01:27:18,989
You had me beaten up.

1358
01:27:19,239 --> 01:27:21,450
That was not supposed to happen.

1359
01:27:21,909 --> 01:27:24,453
Only Simpson. You walked in,
it was bad timing.

1360
01:27:24,578 --> 01:27:25,787
Bad timing?

1361
01:27:29,291 --> 01:27:30,751
Humson will testify.

1362
01:27:30,918 --> 01:27:33,629
Why, James?
Humson doesn't know anything!

1363
01:27:34,505 --> 01:27:38,550
He runs three prisons. He has to know
something. Unless he's never there.

1364
01:27:43,180 --> 01:27:44,473
Son of a bitch.

1365
01:27:49,019 --> 01:27:50,646
He was never there.

1366
01:27:51,188 --> 01:27:52,272
Never there.

1367
01:27:52,356 --> 01:27:53,857
You never saw him?

1368
01:27:54,024 --> 01:27:57,277
You'd hear about him visiting,
but l never saw him.

1369
01:27:58,820 --> 01:28:01,990
Your own brother did that to you?
Your brother did that to you?

1370
01:28:02,115 --> 01:28:04,243
Jesus, rich people are weird.

1371
01:28:06,203 --> 01:28:10,332
You hear DiMaggio broke Keeler's record?
Forty-five straight games.

1372
01:28:11,124 --> 01:28:13,210
Wouldn't it be great if he never stopped?

1373
01:28:13,335 --> 01:28:15,254
Dock records would show his visits.

1374
01:28:15,337 --> 01:28:19,007
Every trip is recorded. l had to sign in
myself that one time l went.

1375
01:28:19,132 --> 01:28:20,926
-What?
-We're friends, huh?

1376
01:28:21,134 --> 01:28:22,177
Yeah, sure.

1377
01:28:22,386 --> 01:28:24,137
ls it over? l mean, you know?

1378
01:28:24,221 --> 01:28:25,347
ls that all?

1379
01:28:25,973 --> 01:28:28,684
Nothing more you're going to do
with the trial?

1380
01:28:29,059 --> 01:28:30,519
Thought you didn't care.

1381
01:28:30,561 --> 01:28:31,937
No, l don't care.

1382
01:28:32,145 --> 01:28:36,149
lt's just that as long as you got shit
to throw at them, we can keep talking.

1383
01:28:36,233 --> 01:28:38,151
But when it's over, it's over.

1384
01:28:38,235 --> 01:28:41,029
l'm not here to entertain you
until the executioner comes.

1385
01:28:41,113 --> 01:28:43,031
This trial isn't a game.

1386
01:28:48,495 --> 01:28:51,123
lf l was on the outside, if there was...

1387
01:28:51,874 --> 01:28:55,794
...a good fairy and she waved a wand
and l was on the outside...

1388
01:28:56,086 --> 01:28:58,463
...you and me, would we be friends then?

1389
01:28:59,006 --> 01:28:59,965
Yes.

1390
01:29:00,215 --> 01:29:02,676
No, no, no, we wouldn't.

1391
01:29:03,093 --> 01:29:06,346
You wouldn't have nothing to do with me.
You know it.

1392
01:29:06,513 --> 01:29:09,224
What l can't figure out is why. l mean...

1393
01:29:09,683 --> 01:29:13,645
...we both ain't got nobody else
and we're the same age, sort of.

1394
01:29:14,605 --> 01:29:17,065
lf l'd have lived in your house...

1395
01:29:17,274 --> 01:29:20,485
...and they'd have switched us
when we was babies...

1396
01:29:21,445 --> 01:29:23,906
...l could have been just like you.

1397
01:29:24,239 --> 01:29:26,074
lf they stuck you in the hole...

1398
01:29:28,118 --> 01:29:29,912
...you could be sitting here...

1399
01:29:30,037 --> 01:29:33,207
...like me, asking why we couldn't
be friends on the outside.

1400
01:29:33,290 --> 01:29:35,292
You ever steal five bucks?

1401
01:29:38,795 --> 01:29:39,880
Once.

1402
01:29:40,631 --> 01:29:42,424
When l was a kid, from my...

1403
01:29:42,925 --> 01:29:44,635
...brother's wallet.

1404
01:29:45,886 --> 01:29:46,845
What happened?

1405
01:29:49,431 --> 01:29:51,600
He told me not to do it again.

1406
01:29:54,978 --> 01:29:58,023
Why'd they put me in that hole
for three years?

1407
01:29:59,441 --> 01:30:01,610
l could have been just like you.

1408
01:30:04,488 --> 01:30:06,657
l'd just like to ask them, you know.

1409
01:30:21,338 --> 01:30:22,923
<i>Raise your right hand.</i>

1410
01:30:24,258 --> 01:30:27,803
<i>Do you swear to tell the whole truth
and nothing but the truth?</i>

1411
01:30:28,095 --> 01:30:29,555
<i>So help me God.</i>

1412
01:30:29,972 --> 01:30:31,557
You may be seated.

1413
01:30:36,603 --> 01:30:40,816
Warden Humson, in a book you wrote,
you refer to the convicts as your children.

1414
01:30:41,358 --> 01:30:45,362
You liken your job to that of a parent,
providing for their physical needs...

1415
01:30:45,487 --> 01:30:47,447
...and molding their character.

1416
01:30:47,698 --> 01:30:49,324
Yes, l wrote that.

1417
01:30:49,783 --> 01:30:52,035
l have a record of a prisoner
named Johnson...

1418
01:30:52,160 --> 01:30:54,788
...who did a total of 500 days
in the lower cells.

1419
01:30:54,872 --> 01:30:56,498
The hole, the dungeon.

1420
01:30:57,291 --> 01:31:01,712
This was over a ten-year period for such
offenses as not finishing all his food...

1421
01:31:02,212 --> 01:31:06,091
...having an extra pair of socks in his cell,
keeping an untidy cell...

1422
01:31:06,633 --> 01:31:10,762
...smuggling food from the dining room,
crumbs, in fact, for a pet lizard.

1423
01:31:11,013 --> 01:31:13,265
ls this what you mean
''molding character''?

1424
01:31:13,807 --> 01:31:15,100
No, no, no.

1425
01:31:15,309 --> 01:31:17,102
You're twisting things here.

1426
01:31:17,311 --> 01:31:22,024
The isolation cells were simply a tool
of a temporary nature...

1427
01:31:22,524 --> 01:31:25,944
...for extreme cases
within the general population.

1428
01:31:27,029 --> 01:31:31,658
Moreover, you make it sound like
the prisoner did 1,500 days at one stretch...

1429
01:31:31,909 --> 01:31:33,493
...for one infraction.

1430
01:31:34,578 --> 01:31:36,038
That's not true.

1431
01:31:37,247 --> 01:31:39,082
Prisoners were held...

1432
01:31:39,333 --> 01:31:41,210
...for 19 days at a time.

1433
01:31:42,336 --> 01:31:44,004
-That's all.
-That's all.

1434
01:31:45,088 --> 01:31:49,134
Perhaps you can tell me why Henri Young
did over 1,000 days in the dungeon?

1435
01:31:49,343 --> 01:31:51,720
Not 19 days, but 1,000 days...

1436
01:31:52,346 --> 01:31:55,807
...in total darkness with only 30 minutes
of daylight a year.

1437
01:31:56,058 --> 01:31:57,643
He tried to escape.

1438
01:31:58,060 --> 01:32:02,439
You can't compare his offense with that
of a man who smuggled food to a lizard.

1439
01:32:02,606 --> 01:32:05,943
Was this the first time a sentence
of three years had been imposed?

1440
01:32:06,068 --> 01:32:07,402
lt wasn't a sentence.

1441
01:32:07,486 --> 01:32:10,239
lt was an administrative decision
to place him there...

1442
01:32:10,364 --> 01:32:12,783
...for an undetermined amount of time.

1443
01:32:13,450 --> 01:32:17,246
Why not a time limit? Doesn't that seem
a little bit inhumane? No time limit.

1444
01:32:17,371 --> 01:32:18,872
Put simply, no.

1445
01:32:20,582 --> 01:32:23,043
While we strive to prevent crime...

1446
01:32:23,293 --> 01:32:26,088
...what should we do with a man
who has committed it?

1447
01:32:27,464 --> 01:32:29,967
We aim to make him his better self.

1448
01:32:30,801 --> 01:32:32,302
His better self.

1449
01:32:32,803 --> 01:32:35,931
l'm sure that Henri Young thanks you
for his better self.

1450
01:32:36,139 --> 01:32:40,269
lt's a fact you simply put Henri Young
in that dungeon and forgot all about him.

1451
01:32:40,727 --> 01:32:42,271
Washed your hands of him.

1452
01:32:42,396 --> 01:32:45,816
Henri wanted me to ask you, ''Why?''
Why would you do that, sir? Why?

1453
01:32:45,899 --> 01:32:47,359
That's not true.

1454
01:32:47,609 --> 01:32:48,694
Objection.

1455
01:32:48,902 --> 01:32:51,613
l withdraw the question.
l apologize to the jury--

1456
01:32:51,738 --> 01:32:53,949
lt's not necessary that you apologize.

1457
01:32:54,825 --> 01:32:57,703
Actually, Your Honor, it is.
l made a mistake.

1458
01:32:58,161 --> 01:33:02,124
The warden couldn't simply have washed
his hands of Henri Young...

1459
01:33:02,499 --> 01:33:05,252
...because he had absolutely no idea
he was there.

1460
01:33:05,335 --> 01:33:06,795
lsn't that true?

1461
01:33:06,920 --> 01:33:10,757
You're never there. You permit Glenn
to run that prison any way he sees fit.

1462
01:33:10,841 --> 01:33:14,761
l am there as much as l need to be.
l run three penal institutions.

1463
01:33:15,137 --> 01:33:18,473
lt's impossible to know every detail
of every inmate.

1464
01:33:19,183 --> 01:33:23,729
l have the Port Authority records that you
signed every time you went to Alcatraz.

1465
01:33:24,771 --> 01:33:28,358
You went seven times in '38,
five in '39, ten in '40...

1466
01:33:28,692 --> 01:33:30,694
...and only twice so far this year.

1467
01:33:30,777 --> 01:33:33,030
Twenty-four day trips in over 3-1 /2 years...

1468
01:33:33,155 --> 01:33:36,533
...while Henri Young was in that dungeon
over 1,000 days.

1469
01:33:36,700 --> 01:33:38,869
Twenty-four out of 1,000 days.

1470
01:33:39,203 --> 01:33:41,538
That's how much you needed to be there?

1471
01:33:41,663 --> 01:33:46,043
You knew nothing about a man who was
left to die in a dungeon for 3-1 /2 years.

1472
01:33:46,126 --> 01:33:47,294
Absolutely nothing!

1473
01:33:47,377 --> 01:33:50,756
ln fact, you have never even met
Henri Young, have you?

1474
01:33:51,381 --> 01:33:55,511
Right now, in fact, is the first time
you have ever seen this man! Look at him !

1475
01:33:55,969 --> 01:33:58,472
That's him there! That's Henri Young!
Right there!

1476
01:33:58,597 --> 01:34:00,349
-He tried to escape.
-Yes, he did.

1477
01:34:00,474 --> 01:34:04,561
But the fact, the cold, brutal fact is
that this man...

1478
01:34:04,728 --> 01:34:07,356
...who had never,
never before in his entire life...

1479
01:34:07,481 --> 01:34:10,150
...harmed or attempted to harm
another human being...

1480
01:34:10,234 --> 01:34:11,818
...was now a murderer!

1481
01:34:12,236 --> 01:34:13,445
That is a fact!

1482
01:34:13,570 --> 01:34:15,697
-Yes, but he tried to escape.
-lt's a fact--

1483
01:34:16,698 --> 01:34:20,786
You can't let them get away with this.
lf we let them, where would we be?

1484
01:34:20,994 --> 01:34:25,123
-Should we let murderers roam free?
-Henri Young was not a murderer!

1485
01:34:25,499 --> 01:34:28,919
Henri Young was not a murderer
until Alcatraz got a hold of him !

1486
01:34:29,002 --> 01:34:33,465
The prison runs under your guidelines,
so you created the murderer, didn't you?

1487
01:34:33,715 --> 01:34:34,883
Didn't you?

1488
01:34:36,426 --> 01:34:38,303
He tried to escape.

1489
01:34:40,848 --> 01:34:43,016
That's the thing, you see.

1490
01:34:48,939 --> 01:34:51,942
Do you have any further questions
for this witness?

1491
01:34:54,027 --> 01:34:56,738
-No, Your Honor.
-The witness may step down.

1492
01:34:57,614 --> 01:34:59,241
But he tried to escape.

1493
01:35:00,242 --> 01:35:04,538
<i>I'd been trained all my life for that day.
Control the witness, go for the kill.</i>

1494
01:35:05,372 --> 01:35:06,832
<i>Win, victory.</i>

1495
01:35:08,250 --> 01:35:10,127
<i>School prepared me well.</i>

1496
01:35:10,294 --> 01:35:12,504
<i>My brother, he had prepared me well.</i>

1497
01:35:13,255 --> 01:35:15,841
<i>Years later, he and I would reconcile.</i>

1498
01:35:16,967 --> 01:35:18,760
<i>Family's family, you know.</i>

1499
01:35:20,304 --> 01:35:22,139
<i>Mary congratulated me...</i>

1500
01:35:22,264 --> 01:35:24,725
<i>...but we'd already begun to drift apart.</i>

1501
01:35:26,059 --> 01:35:29,605
<i>When you only try to win,
you sometimes lose sight of the goal...</i>

1502
01:35:30,480 --> 01:35:32,941
<i>...which should have always
remained Henri.</i>

1503
01:35:44,328 --> 01:35:47,539
<i>The most you'll get is
second-degree murder.</i>

1504
01:35:47,831 --> 01:35:49,374
<i>Maybe manslaughter, ten years.</i>

1505
01:35:49,499 --> 01:35:52,085
<i>If you get a recommendation
for clemency, you'll walk.</i>

1506
01:35:52,169 --> 01:35:55,464
-You have your whole life in front of you.
-Monday morning...

1507
01:35:55,797 --> 01:35:59,384
...go up to the judge and tell him
there's been a change of plan.

1508
01:35:59,593 --> 01:36:01,887
l want you to change my plea to guilty.

1509
01:36:03,847 --> 01:36:04,973
ls that a joke?

1510
01:36:05,098 --> 01:36:06,558
Not to me, it's not.

1511
01:36:07,017 --> 01:36:08,393
l'm not doing it.

1512
01:36:08,852 --> 01:36:12,022
What have l been doing here?
Why have l been wasting my time?

1513
01:36:12,814 --> 01:36:14,691
l never thought we'd win.

1514
01:36:15,317 --> 01:36:17,277
l thought you wanted to fight.

1515
01:36:17,444 --> 01:36:18,654
l just...

1516
01:36:19,196 --> 01:36:20,656
...wanted a friend.

1517
01:36:20,822 --> 01:36:22,407
l am your friend.

1518
01:36:22,533 --> 01:36:25,202
No, you're not. lt's always about you.

1519
01:36:26,119 --> 01:36:28,830
lt's never about me.
You don't understand.

1520
01:36:29,164 --> 01:36:32,334
l already lost and you just keep talking...

1521
01:36:32,960 --> 01:36:35,420
...and talking and you never listen.

1522
01:36:35,629 --> 01:36:39,842
You don't know what you're talking about.
You just don't know what it's like.

1523
01:36:40,050 --> 01:36:41,218
What what's like?

1524
01:36:41,343 --> 01:36:42,511
Alcatraz!

1525
01:36:43,720 --> 01:36:47,474
Where do you think they'll send me
for those ten years you're talking about?

1526
01:36:47,558 --> 01:36:49,601
They'll send me back to Alcatraz!

1527
01:36:49,852 --> 01:36:52,104
When it's over, you'll be alive!

1528
01:36:52,229 --> 01:36:53,272
l'm Henri!

1529
01:36:53,856 --> 01:36:56,525
l'm the one that's got to do the time,
not you!

1530
01:36:56,984 --> 01:36:59,319
And l can't do it! l can't do it!

1531
01:36:59,862 --> 01:37:01,530
l can't, all right?

1532
01:37:03,490 --> 01:37:05,033
lt's not worth it.

1533
01:37:05,492 --> 01:37:06,827
lt's not worth it.

1534
01:37:07,578 --> 01:37:09,663
Nothing's worth going back there.

1535
01:37:13,166 --> 01:37:17,004
<i>Sixty-seven thousand fans
at Municipal Stadium in Cleveland...</i>

1536
01:37:17,504 --> 01:37:21,967
<i>...watching to see if Joe DiMaggio can keep
his 56-game hitting streak alive.</i>

1537
01:37:22,176 --> 01:37:26,180
<i>Jim Bank is on the mound,
count one and one, runner on first base.</i>

1538
01:37:27,181 --> 01:37:29,474
<i>Here's the pitch. DiMaggio swings.</i>

1539
01:37:37,024 --> 01:37:40,736
<i>It's a double play! DiMaggio's 56-game
hitting streak is stopped!</i>

1540
01:37:47,701 --> 01:37:49,161
Mrs. Rosetta Dial?

1541
01:38:04,968 --> 01:38:06,470
Why are we in here?

1542
01:38:06,637 --> 01:38:09,681
Maybe there are some things
worth fighting for.

1543
01:38:16,647 --> 01:38:17,689
Henri?

1544
01:38:18,649 --> 01:38:20,108
Do l know you?

1545
01:38:23,654 --> 01:38:25,113
l'm Rosetta, Henri.

1546
01:38:26,657 --> 01:38:28,200
l'm your sister.

1547
01:38:38,502 --> 01:38:40,212
My baby's name is Henri.

1548
01:38:47,094 --> 01:38:48,804
Mr. Stamphill says--

1549
01:38:49,012 --> 01:38:50,222
l was...

1550
01:38:52,474 --> 01:38:54,226
...beginning to think...

1551
01:38:56,603 --> 01:38:58,730
...that you wasn't real. That l...

1552
01:38:59,982 --> 01:39:01,733
...made you up in my mind.

1553
01:39:05,028 --> 01:39:06,655
l want you to come--

1554
01:39:08,532 --> 01:39:10,993
l want you to tell Jim that l appreciate...

1555
01:39:11,118 --> 01:39:13,579
...him bringing you down here
and knowing...

1556
01:39:13,787 --> 01:39:15,664
...that you turned out okay.

1557
01:39:16,623 --> 01:39:20,544
That means a lot. l want you to tell him,
come Monday morning...

1558
01:39:21,712 --> 01:39:24,673
...he's going to plead me guilty
just like l said.

1559
01:39:28,552 --> 01:39:30,179
l wish l wasn't...

1560
01:39:30,554 --> 01:39:32,681
...so scared of them, Rosetta.

1561
01:39:35,726 --> 01:39:37,477
l wish to God l wasn't.

1562
01:39:55,662 --> 01:39:57,581
You take care of yourself now.

1563
01:42:01,205 --> 01:42:03,207
<i>You may call your next witness.</i>

1564
01:42:04,041 --> 01:42:05,501
Just a second.

1565
01:42:06,919 --> 01:42:07,961
l'm your friend.

1566
01:42:08,128 --> 01:42:10,756
On the outside, l'd be lucky
to consider you my friend.

1567
01:42:10,881 --> 01:42:12,591
So l'm not going to kill you.

1568
01:42:12,716 --> 01:42:16,303
-Are you going to call a witness today?
-Yes, Your Honor.

1569
01:42:17,554 --> 01:42:21,350
lf you want to change your plea,
you go do it. l'm not going to do it.

1570
01:42:21,433 --> 01:42:24,269
-l want you to plead me guilty.
-l don't think you are.

1571
01:42:24,394 --> 01:42:25,854
-Doesn't matter.
-Does to me.

1572
01:42:25,938 --> 01:42:28,857
Counselor, l am very close to finding you
in contempt of--

1573
01:42:28,941 --> 01:42:31,193
The defense calls Mr. Henri Young.

1574
01:42:31,443 --> 01:42:32,402
No!

1575
01:42:32,736 --> 01:42:34,196
He just lost the case.

1576
01:42:34,279 --> 01:42:36,240
You go up and change your plea.

1577
01:42:36,448 --> 01:42:38,909
l repeat, l'm not going to do it for you.

1578
01:42:40,744 --> 01:42:41,745
Counselor--

1579
01:42:42,412 --> 01:42:43,747
He's coming.

1580
01:42:45,457 --> 01:42:46,750
Go ahead, tell them.

1581
01:42:55,926 --> 01:42:57,386
Tell them, not me.

1582
01:43:02,140 --> 01:43:03,976
Better ask the right questions.

1583
01:43:04,101 --> 01:43:06,562
-l'll ask what l want.
-l'll answer what l want.

1584
01:43:06,687 --> 01:43:08,063
-Fine.
-Fine.

1585
01:43:12,484 --> 01:43:14,736
Guilty, guilty, guilty, guilty.

1586
01:43:19,992 --> 01:43:20,993
Stand up.

1587
01:43:21,451 --> 01:43:23,203
Put your hand on the Bible.

1588
01:43:26,957 --> 01:43:31,086
Do you swear to tell the truth, and nothing
but the truth, so help you God?

1589
01:43:31,253 --> 01:43:32,421
So help me God.

1590
01:43:32,504 --> 01:43:33,797
State your name.

1591
01:43:34,006 --> 01:43:35,382
Henri Young.

1592
01:43:35,632 --> 01:43:36,800
Be seated.

1593
01:43:37,634 --> 01:43:38,760
Your Honor--

1594
01:43:38,844 --> 01:43:40,596
Wait until l've asked a question!

1595
01:43:40,679 --> 01:43:43,140
-l haven't asked you yet.
-He's trying to trick me.

1596
01:43:43,223 --> 01:43:46,852
Please instruct the witness to remain silent
until l ask a question...

1597
01:43:46,977 --> 01:43:49,104
...and only answer the question l ask.

1598
01:43:49,188 --> 01:43:50,314
He's your witness.

1599
01:43:50,856 --> 01:43:51,899
He won't listen.

1600
01:43:52,149 --> 01:43:53,567
He's trying to trick me!

1601
01:43:53,650 --> 01:43:54,943
Silence, Mr. Young.

1602
01:43:55,819 --> 01:43:59,448
Here's the way it works.
Mr. Stamphill will ask you a question...

1603
01:43:59,656 --> 01:44:01,450
...and you answer that question.

1604
01:44:01,533 --> 01:44:05,996
However, Mr. Stamphill cannot coerce you
into testifying against yourself.

1605
01:44:06,205 --> 01:44:07,748
You do understand that?

1606
01:44:07,873 --> 01:44:09,416
Yeah, l just want to--

1607
01:44:09,875 --> 01:44:13,921
Did we have a conversation in which
you said you wish to change your plea--

1608
01:44:15,214 --> 01:44:18,842
You will wait until l have finished
instructing the witness.

1609
01:44:19,218 --> 01:44:21,261
lt's okay. l wanted him to ask that.

1610
01:44:21,553 --> 01:44:23,055
lt is not okay.

1611
01:44:24,056 --> 01:44:28,435
And l do not need you to tell me
what is or is not okay.

1612
01:44:29,520 --> 01:44:31,939
ln this courtroom,
l am the one who decides...

1613
01:44:32,022 --> 01:44:34,191
...what is or is not okay.

1614
01:44:35,275 --> 01:44:35,984
Okay?

1615
01:44:37,194 --> 01:44:37,819
Yes.

1616
01:44:38,028 --> 01:44:39,488
Thank you very much.

1617
01:44:42,032 --> 01:44:43,992
Counselors, approach the bench.

1618
01:44:48,205 --> 01:44:51,166
Do you mind telling me
what the hell is going on here?

1619
01:44:51,250 --> 01:44:52,167
l'm trying--

1620
01:44:52,251 --> 01:44:55,504
Your own defendant is looking to me
to protect him from you.

1621
01:44:55,629 --> 01:44:56,922
So what's going on?

1622
01:44:57,047 --> 01:44:59,466
l know it seems very strange but--

1623
01:44:59,716 --> 01:45:03,512
ln my opinion, you're an idiot to put him
on the stand for any reason.

1624
01:45:03,595 --> 01:45:06,014
You're asking him to testify
against himself.

1625
01:45:06,431 --> 01:45:10,269
lt doesn't seem to make sense,
but the prosecution isn't objecting so--

1626
01:45:10,394 --> 01:45:12,020
No, l'm not. Let him continue.

1627
01:45:12,271 --> 01:45:13,397
Shut up.

1628
01:45:14,898 --> 01:45:18,235
Enough damage has been done.
l can't make it any worse.

1629
01:45:18,443 --> 01:45:19,653
Yes, you can.

1630
01:45:20,779 --> 01:45:23,740
All right. But you're on a very short leash.

1631
01:45:24,783 --> 01:45:26,410
A very short leash.

1632
01:45:26,743 --> 01:45:29,705
l will throw you in jail
for contempt myself.

1633
01:45:30,622 --> 01:45:31,582
Now...

1634
01:45:31,790 --> 01:45:34,418
...let's get this goddamn show on the road.

1635
01:45:38,046 --> 01:45:39,756
l think you're doing a great job.

1636
01:45:42,092 --> 01:45:44,428
Mr. Young, stop playing with that!

1637
01:45:47,931 --> 01:45:51,852
Now, do you or do you not wish
to continue testifying, Mr. Young?

1638
01:45:52,644 --> 01:45:55,105
lt's okay. He asked me the right question.

1639
01:45:55,939 --> 01:45:57,941
Counselor, you may proceed.

1640
01:46:01,153 --> 01:46:04,781
Mr. Young, did you and l not have
a conversation last Friday...

1641
01:46:04,990 --> 01:46:08,118
...in which you told me you wished
to change your plea to guilty?

1642
01:46:08,493 --> 01:46:10,078
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

1643
01:46:11,496 --> 01:46:14,249
l want to change my plea.
That's what l said.

1644
01:46:14,458 --> 01:46:18,170
l'm going to ask you the single
most important question l can ask you.

1645
01:46:18,295 --> 01:46:20,088
lt's what this whole trial's about.

1646
01:46:20,631 --> 01:46:23,467
Are you guilty of the murder
of Rufus McCain?

1647
01:46:23,675 --> 01:46:26,178
l want to change my plea to guilty.
l said that.

1648
01:46:26,303 --> 01:46:29,431
l didn't ask what you wanted to do.
l asked if you are guilty.

1649
01:46:29,556 --> 01:46:30,349
Objection!

1650
01:46:30,474 --> 01:46:32,184
He's badgering the witness.

1651
01:46:32,309 --> 01:46:35,103
-He's my witness, for Christ's sake!
-l'm not your nothing!

1652
01:46:35,187 --> 01:46:38,232
lf the accused wants to enter
a plea of guilty--

1653
01:46:38,649 --> 01:46:42,486
Silence! Mr. Stamphill,
you are skating on very thin ice here.

1654
01:46:43,487 --> 01:46:46,615
Maybe, Your Honor,
but l'd like to get to the other side.

1655
01:46:48,492 --> 01:46:50,619
Very well. You may proceed...

1656
01:46:50,994 --> 01:46:52,788
...at your own peril.

1657
01:46:52,871 --> 01:46:53,789
Thank you.

1658
01:46:57,501 --> 01:46:59,795
Let me take this one step at a time.

1659
01:47:02,840 --> 01:47:05,509
We had a conversation in which
l told you l felt...

1660
01:47:05,634 --> 01:47:07,594
...with the way the trial was going...

1661
01:47:07,678 --> 01:47:12,099
...the most you'd have to face, more than
likely, would be another ten years or less.

1662
01:47:12,391 --> 01:47:14,810
-l don't care--
-Ten years, that's what l said.

1663
01:47:14,893 --> 01:47:16,353
Yeah, yeah, but--

1664
01:47:16,562 --> 01:47:18,313
Did you say to me...

1665
01:47:18,522 --> 01:47:21,692
...you were the guy who had to do
the time, not me?

1666
01:47:21,900 --> 01:47:25,070
That they'd stick you back in Alcatraz
for those ten years, right?

1667
01:47:25,195 --> 01:47:28,198
That's what l told you.
Why are you doing this to me?

1668
01:47:28,407 --> 01:47:32,202
Because if you change your plea to guilty,
they will execute you.

1669
01:47:32,411 --> 01:47:34,538
-You will die!
-So fucking what?

1670
01:47:34,872 --> 01:47:36,999
l'd rather die than go back there!

1671
01:47:49,761 --> 01:47:51,013
What'd you say?

1672
01:47:51,221 --> 01:47:52,181
l said...

1673
01:47:53,891 --> 01:47:57,311
...l'd rather die than go back there!
Can't you understand that?

1674
01:47:58,395 --> 01:47:59,521
Why, Henri?

1675
01:47:59,730 --> 01:48:01,398
Why do you want to die?

1676
01:48:01,940 --> 01:48:03,233
Because....

1677
01:48:05,110 --> 01:48:06,361
Because l'm...

1678
01:48:08,405 --> 01:48:09,740
...scared of them.

1679
01:48:10,616 --> 01:48:13,035
l'm scared to go back there. l'm scared.

1680
01:48:13,952 --> 01:48:15,746
l'm scared. l'm scared.

1681
01:48:15,954 --> 01:48:19,166
-Objection! He's finished--
-l haven't finished anything!

1682
01:48:19,791 --> 01:48:21,418
Henri, look at me.

1683
01:48:21,793 --> 01:48:23,879
Henri, look at me. Look at me.

1684
01:48:24,463 --> 01:48:27,925
You were right. You were right,
l was wrong. l'm sorry.

1685
01:48:28,133 --> 01:48:31,136
l'm just talking to you right now.
Not the judge or the jury.

1686
01:48:31,261 --> 01:48:34,389
lf you want to die, we'll back you up.
But l swear to God...

1687
01:48:34,473 --> 01:48:37,893
...l'll fight these bastards
so they'll never do this to anyone again.

1688
01:48:37,976 --> 01:48:40,020
You're not going to die for nothing!

1689
01:48:40,145 --> 01:48:41,605
The choice is yours.

1690
01:48:42,940 --> 01:48:44,566
What do you want to do?

1691
01:48:50,280 --> 01:48:52,241
l want to stop being afraid.

1692
01:49:00,624 --> 01:49:01,625
All right.

1693
01:49:36,827 --> 01:49:38,120
Henri Young...

1694
01:49:40,664 --> 01:49:43,542
...are you guilty of the murder
of Rufus McCain?

1695
01:50:04,730 --> 01:50:06,148
l was the weapon...

1696
01:50:07,649 --> 01:50:09,568
...but l ain't no killer.

1697
01:50:12,237 --> 01:50:13,864
They're the murderers.

1698
01:50:25,209 --> 01:50:27,753
Bailiff, you may remove the prisoner.

1699
01:50:29,671 --> 01:50:32,049
Escort the prisoner to the holding room.

1700
01:50:59,451 --> 01:51:03,705
<i>Ladies and gentlemen of the jury,
you have received your instructions.</i>

1701
01:51:03,956 --> 01:51:07,876
<i>You may find the defendant guilty
of involuntary manslaughter...</i>

1702
01:51:07,960 --> 01:51:11,338
<i>...which carries with it a maximum penalty
of three years...</i>

1703
01:51:11,713 --> 01:51:14,341
<i>...in which case the defendant
will be remanded...</i>

1704
01:51:14,424 --> 01:51:17,052
<i>...to the custody of the warden of Alcatraz.</i>

1705
01:51:18,011 --> 01:51:22,099
<i>Or you may find the defendant guilty
of murder in the first degree.</i>

1706
01:51:23,267 --> 01:51:25,727
<i>Without a recommendation for mercy...</i>

1707
01:51:25,811 --> 01:51:28,897
<i>...that verdict will carry with it
a sentence of death.</i>

1708
01:52:18,530 --> 01:52:20,449
This court is now in session.

1709
01:52:21,491 --> 01:52:24,620
Ladies and gentlemen of the jury,
how do you find?

1710
01:52:25,537 --> 01:52:27,164
The defendant will rise.

1711
01:52:29,499 --> 01:52:32,503
We, the jury,
find the defendant, Henri Young...

1712
01:52:32,711 --> 01:52:35,172
...not guilty of first-degree murder...

1713
01:52:35,506 --> 01:52:38,050
...and guilty only
of involuntary manslaughter.

1714
01:52:38,175 --> 01:52:39,635
Order! Order!

1715
01:52:40,177 --> 01:52:43,472
We would like permission to address
the court, if possible.

1716
01:52:44,181 --> 01:52:45,349
Very well.

1717
01:52:45,557 --> 01:52:49,811
We have this day signed a petition
which l would like to read to the court.

1718
01:52:51,230 --> 01:52:55,150
''We would like the following to be read
into the record of this proceeding.

1719
01:52:55,234 --> 01:52:58,487
''Though we know it will have
no legal or binding effect...

1720
01:52:59,363 --> 01:53:02,199
''...we'd hope that it will have
a moral effect.

1721
01:53:03,534 --> 01:53:07,788
''We, the members of the jury,
recommend the immediate investigation...

1722
01:53:07,871 --> 01:53:10,249
''...by the proper federal authorities...

1723
01:53:10,374 --> 01:53:13,502
''...of the federal penitentiary
known as Alcatraz.

1724
01:53:14,253 --> 01:53:17,005
''We find this institution, its wardens...

1725
01:53:17,548 --> 01:53:20,968
''...and associate warden,
guilty of crimes against humanity.''

1726
01:53:22,761 --> 01:53:23,887
Thank you.

1727
01:53:24,096 --> 01:53:25,639
The jury is dismissed.

1728
01:53:25,764 --> 01:53:27,724
This trial is concluded.

1729
01:53:27,808 --> 01:53:30,811
All rise. The defendant is remanded
to the custody of Alcatraz.

1730
01:53:32,229 --> 01:53:35,440
<i>News from San Francisco.
The Young trial concludes.</i>

1731
01:53:35,774 --> 01:53:38,402
<i>The Rock will be investigated
as Young is vindicated...</i>

1732
01:53:38,527 --> 01:53:41,071
<i>...by a verdict of involuntary manslaughter.</i>

1733
01:53:41,780 --> 01:53:44,116
<i>As I walked out of the courtroom
that day...</i>

1734
01:53:44,449 --> 01:53:48,412
<i>...I did not fully realize how much
Henri and I had actually accomplished.</i>

1735
01:53:48,579 --> 01:53:50,414
<i>It all just happened so fast.</i>

1736
01:53:51,748 --> 01:53:53,876
l'll to be up to see you as often as l can.

1737
01:53:54,001 --> 01:53:56,920
Then you can bring that Blanche back
for a second shot.

1738
01:53:57,129 --> 01:53:58,881
l'll see what l can do.

1739
01:53:59,047 --> 01:54:00,382
No place like home.

1740
01:54:00,465 --> 01:54:01,925
Henri, it's not over.

1741
01:54:02,801 --> 01:54:06,263
l'm going to appeal to have you moved
to another prison.

1742
01:54:06,471 --> 01:54:09,474
l'm going to file motions to have
your original case reopened.

1743
01:54:09,600 --> 01:54:12,060
Henri and Jim, together again, huh?

1744
01:54:12,269 --> 01:54:14,646
That's right. Henri and Jim,
together again.

1745
01:54:15,439 --> 01:54:17,316
Henri and Jim, together again.

1746
01:54:18,275 --> 01:54:19,735
l won, didn't l?

1747
01:54:19,902 --> 01:54:22,154
l mean, l really did something.

1748
01:54:22,529 --> 01:54:23,530
l won!

1749
01:54:24,448 --> 01:54:26,241
That's right, you won.

1750
01:54:28,619 --> 01:54:31,121
How many games was
DiMaggio's hitting streak?

1751
01:54:31,330 --> 01:54:32,664
Fifty-four?

1752
01:54:32,915 --> 01:54:34,416
No, l got you.

1753
01:54:34,625 --> 01:54:36,376
lt was 56, wasn't it?

1754
01:54:40,339 --> 01:54:41,798
l'll see you soon!

1755
01:54:43,300 --> 01:54:44,843
Take care of yourself.

1756
01:55:02,069 --> 01:55:03,862
<i>The definition of victory is:</i>

1757
01:55:04,488 --> 01:55:06,949
<i>''Success in any contest or struggle.</i>

1758
01:55:08,200 --> 01:55:10,452
<i>''An engagement ending in triumph.''</i>

1759
01:55:20,712 --> 01:55:24,258
<i>That was to be the last time
I was to see Henri Young alive.</i>

1760
01:55:25,133 --> 01:55:29,179
<i>Before the court date was set for
an appeal, his body was found in a cell.</i>

1761
01:55:30,055 --> 01:55:33,308
<i>He laid beneath a single word
he had scrawled with a rock:</i>

1762
01:55:34,685 --> 01:55:35,811
<i>''Victory.''</i>

1763
01:55:37,312 --> 01:55:40,190
<i>Henri Young had taught me
the meaning of the word.</i>

1764
01:55:51,243 --> 01:55:54,788
<i>He was the only man that I have known
who gave more than he asked.</i>

1765
01:55:55,080 --> 01:55:57,332
<i>All that he ever wanted was a friend.</i>

1766
01:55:57,916 --> 01:56:01,712
<i>I will always remember him
as one of the best friends I have ever had.</i>

1767
01:56:03,589 --> 01:56:06,133
<i>Unlike many men that live much longer...</i>

1768
01:56:06,717 --> 01:56:08,844
<i>...Henri Young did not die in vain.</i>

1769
01:56:10,429 --> 01:56:12,556
<i>In the end, he was not afraid.</i>

1770
01:56:13,891 --> 01:56:15,893
<i>He lived and he died in triumph.</i>

1771
01:56:18,770 --> 01:56:20,731
<i>If only we could all do that.</i>

1772
01:56:30,282 --> 01:56:31,700
Welcome home.

1773
01:56:33,577 --> 01:56:35,037
l've missed you.

1774
01:56:44,046 --> 01:56:45,589
You can beat me...

1775
01:56:46,048 --> 01:56:49,718
...you can put me back in that hole,
whatever you want to do.

1776
01:56:51,053 --> 01:56:52,763
lt doesn't matter to me.

1777
01:56:54,765 --> 01:56:55,724
Action:

1778
01:56:56,808 --> 01:56:57,935
l won.

1779
01:56:59,228 --> 01:57:00,479
Reaction:

1780
01:57:01,355 --> 01:57:03,690
You can't ever take that away from me.

1781
01:57:19,248 --> 01:57:21,041
Take him to the hole!

1782
01:57:42,646 --> 01:57:46,483
<i>Charles Dickens once said
that solitary confinement was inhumane.</i>

1783
01:57:47,109 --> 01:57:50,112
<i>Seven months later,
the Supreme Court agreed.</i>

1784
01:57:50,654 --> 01:57:54,950
<i>And as a result of the facts brought out
in the trial of The People vs. Young...</i>

1785
01:57:55,033 --> 01:57:57,953
<i>...the dungeons of Alcatraz
were closed forever.</i>

1786
01:57:58,370 --> 01:58:01,999
<i>Associate Warden Glenn was brought up
on charges of mistreatment.</i>

1787
01:58:02,374 --> 01:58:06,170
<i>He was found guilty. He would never work
in the penal system again.</i>

1788
01:58:07,087 --> 01:58:09,047
<i>I remained in private practice.</i>

1789
01:58:10,048 --> 01:58:11,884
<i>I also became a baseball fan.</i>

1790
01:58:13,844 --> 01:58:15,345
<i>You did it, Henri.</i>

